{"title_page": "Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the arts and cultural heritage", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{current related||2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Globalize|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n[[File:Closed library - Island Bay.jpg|alt=|thumb|300x300px|Announcement posted in the door of a [[public library]] in [[Island Bay, New Zealand]] that it is closed due to the pandemic, and will waive all [[Late fees|late return fees]].]]\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] had a substantial impact on the [[performing arts]] and cultural heritage ([[GLAM (industry sector)|GLAM]]) sectors. The global health crisis and the uncertainly resulting from it profoundly affected organisations' operations as well as individuals \u2013 both employed and independent \u2013 across the sector. Arts and culture sector organisations attempted to uphold their (often publicly funded) mission to provide access to cultural heritage to the community, maintain the safety of their employees and the public, and support artists where possible.\n\nBy March 2020, across the world and to varying degrees, museums, performance venues, and other cultural institutions had been indefinitely closed with their exhibitions, events and performances cancelled or postponed. In response there were intensive efforts to provide alternative services through digital platforms, and an awareness that there would be much new cultural work being produced which had been inspired by the events.\n\nMany individuals across the sector would temporarily or permanently lose contracts or employment with varying degrees of warning and financial assistance available, equally, financial stimulus from governments, and charities for artists, would provide greatly differing levels of support depending on the sector and the country.\n\n==Closures== \nThrough the first months of 2020, arts and culture sector organisations around the world progressively restricted their public activities and closed completely due to the coronavirus pandemic. Starting with China, and East-Asia, by mid-to-late March most organisations worldwide had either closed voluntarily or by government mandate. This included museums,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/here-are-the-museums-that-have-closed-due-to-coronavirus|title=Here are the museums that have closed (so far) due to coronavirus|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artnews.com/art-news/news/coronavirus-museum-closures-worldwide-1202680933/|title=See a List of Coronavirus-Related Closures at Museums Around the World|last=Solomon|first=Claire Selvin,Tessa|last2=Selvin|first2=Claire|date=2020-03-12|website=ARTnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26|last3=Solomon|first3=Tessa}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/document/d/1LNCETkPjgcNdmybrwE5g2JEK4KpIfhKThnws1QqgjqE/mobilebasic|title=Museum Responses - COVID-19|website=docs.google.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> theatre and stage productions,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2020/mar/13/coronavirus-culture-arts-films-gigs-festivals-cancellations|title=Coronavirus and culture \u2013 a list of major cancellations|date=2020-03-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-26|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and arts festivals.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/here-are-the-museums-that-have-closed-due-to-coronavirus|title=Here are the museums that have closed (so far) due to coronavirus|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 2020, dates for re-opening and expectations for when cultural organisation can fully \"return to normal\" are unknown for most of the world. Survey data from March in the USA indicated that, when museums were permitted to reopen, the public \"intent to visit\" metric for cultural activities should be unchanged overall from prior to the pandemic \u2013 but with a shifted preference for the ''kind'' of activity. Data indicated there would be a decreased willingness for attendance of activities in confined spaces, large immobile groups (such as cinemas), or tactile activities; with an increase in interest for activities outdoors or with large spaces (such as zoos and botanic gardens).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.colleendilen.com/2020/03/25/how-is-covid-19-impacting-likelihood-to-attend-different-cultural-entities-data/|title=Post-Pandemic, Which Cultural Entity Types Are People More Likely to Revisit? (DATA)|date=2020-03-25|website=Colleen Dilenschneider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.colleendilen.com/2020/03/23/weekly-data-update-how-covid-19-is-impacting-intentions-to-visit-cultural-entities-march-23-2020/|title=DATA UPDATE: How COVID-19 is Impacting Intentions to Visit Cultural Entities - March 23, 2020|date=2020-03-23|website=Colleen Dilenschneider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n''The following is a list of notable closures, announcements and policies affecting the cultural sector.<br>For comprehensive lists:''\n{{See also|List of public venues and institutions closed during the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic}} \n{{See also|List of events affected by the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n'''Africa'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Egypt}}. From March 23 until March 31, 2020 all museums and archaeological sites in Egypt were closed to the public for sterilization and disinfection. During this period a programme to raise the awareness of the sites and museums\u2019 employees on ways of prevention and protection against the virus took place.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cairoscene.com/Buzz/Egypt-to-Close-All-Museums-and-Archaeological-Sites|title= Egypt to close all museums and archaeological sites}}</ref>\n\n'''Asia'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |China}}. On 23 January 2020 all museums were closed throughout mainland China, As the first country for the virus to spread, China was also the first to close its GLAMs.<ref name=\":0\" /> By Mid-March Chinese institutions had slowly and cautiously begun to allow various public activities to be restored with the [[Shanghai Museum]] and the [[Power Station of Art]] (also in Shanghai) reopening on the 13th. Both had restricted visitor numbers and the latter noted that, \u201cWe have also prepared a temporary quarantine area on every floor in case of any emergencies. All visitors must have their temperature taken, as well as present their ID card and registered health code, before entering.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artnews.com/art-news/news/china-japan-south-korea-museums-reopen-coronavirus-1202680994/|title=Museums in China, South Korea, Japan Begin to Reopen After Coronavirus Lockdown|last=Solomon|first=Tessa|last2=Solomon|first2=Tessa|date=2020-03-13|website=ARTnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Some other private galleries in China had begun to open, as had some institutions in South Korea and Japan with limited service (such as by private tour only). By the end of the month 40% of mainland China's tourism attractions had reopened yet most art venues remained closed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/china-south-korea-and-japan-start-to-reopen-museums|title=China, South Korea and Japan start to reopen museums after strict coronavirus lockdown|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n:{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Hong Kong}}. Following the mainland, Hong Kong closed its museums five days later.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Japan}}. On 28 February Japan announced all museums would be closed \"until 17 March\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in|Qatar}}. Qatar museums run by the state closed on 12 March. A forthcoming collaborative show on Picasso's Studio's due to be held by the [[Fire Station (gallery)|Fire Station]] and [[Mus\u00e9e Picasso]] has been indefinitely postponed.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |South Korea}}. On 23 February, one month after mainland China, South Korea closed all museums \"until further notice\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n'''Europe'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts -->\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Austria}}. All federal public museums were closed by directors in response to government precautionary measures banning large events and arrivals from Italy. The [[Albertina Modern]] museum was supposed to open on 13 March but this opening was indefinitely postponed.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Belgium}}. All cultural activities regardless of size were banned by the government from 14 March, which involved the closure of the [[Jan van Eyck]] exhibition at the [[Museum of Fine Arts, Ghent]].<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |France}}. Weeks earlier than French government regulations required it, staff of [[The Louvre]] \"almost unanimously\" voted to force the closure of the museum on the 1st of March, due to concerns for their own health.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51697644|title=Staff force Louvre closure over coronavirus fears|date=2020-03-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> It closed for three days, reopened,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Coronavirus: Louvre museum in Paris reopens after staff walkout|url=https://www.thelocal.fr/20200301/frances-louvre-museum-closed-due-to-virus-fears|website=www.thelocal.fr|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> accepted only visitors with pre-booked tickets from the 9th,<ref name=\":0\" /> then closed definitively on the 13th by government mandate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200313-france-s-louvre-museum-and-versailles-palace-to-shut-over-coronavirus-crisis|title=Louvre, Versailles and Eiffel Tower close over coronavirus crisis|date=2020-03-13|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Reconstruction of the [[Notre-Dame de Paris|Notre-Dame cathedral]] following [[Notre-Dame de Paris fire|the 2019 fire]] was also halted because of worker security.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Germany}}. On 16 March 2020, the German chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] announced in a press conference that the government and [[minister-president]]s had together agreed upon guidelines to limit social contacts in public spaces. Theatres, opera houses, concert halls, museums, exhibition spaces, cinemas, amusement parks and zoos needed to close.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bundesregierung.de/breg-de/themen/coronavirus/leitlinien-bund-laender-1731000|title=Leitlinien gegen Ausbreitung des Coronavirus|date=2020-03-16|website=Die Bundesregierung|language=de|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Italy}}. As the worst hit country in Europe during February and March, national closures were announced on the 23rd of February with an initial reopening date of 1 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/la-cultura-chiusa-tempi-coronavirus-ACNKCpLB|title=La cultura chiusa ai tempi del coronavirus|website=Il Sole 24 ORE|language=it|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Museums outside the \"red zone\" of highly infected areas in the North were then permitted to re-open as long as visitors stayed 1 meter apart,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/italian-museums-reopen-following-government-green-light|title=Coronavirus: Louvre closes while Italian museums reopen following government green light|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> this was later rescinded and all institution were closed until at least 3 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/rome-s-blockbuster-raphael-exhibition-closes|title=Coronavirus in Italy: Ai Weiwei criticised for 'insensitive' pasta meme and Raphael blockbuster closes|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Netherlands}}. On 12 March, Amsterdam's [[Rijksmuseum]] and [[Van Gogh Museum]] announced they would close until at least the end of that month.<ref name=\":0\" /> The following day, having previously announced the reading room and exhibition would remain open, the [[Nationaal Archief|National Archives]] announced their complete closure until April 6.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationaalarchief.nl/beleven/nieuws/studiezaal-en-tentoonstelling-nationaal-archief-tijdelijk-gesloten|title=Studiezaal en tentoonstelling Nationaal Archief tijdelijk gesloten|website=Nationaal Archief|language=nl|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>  On 30 March, the painting ''[[The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen]]'' (1884) by [[Vincent van Gogh]] was stolen from the [[Singer Laren|Singer Laren museum]] while the museum was closed.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/europe/i-m-absolutely-livid-van-gogh-painting-stolen-from-museum-during-pandemic-20200331-p54fgd.html|title='I'm absolutely livid': Van Gogh painting stolen from museum during pandemic|date=31 March 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Poland}}. On 11 March a regional government \"recommendation\" was made that all cultural venues in the [[Tricity, Poland|tricity]] area be closed for two weeks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kultura.trojmiasto.pl/Teatry-odwolane-imprezy-spektakle-koronawirus-w-Trojmiescie-n143084.html|title=Teatry zamkni\u0119te przynajmniej na 2 tygodnie|date=2020-03-10|website=trojmiasto.pl|language=pl|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Museums, including the [[Auschwitz-Birkenau State Museum]], and other cultural venues such as theatres and cinemas were then closed by the national government with an initial re-opening date of 25 March.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Russia}}. The [[Garage Museum of Contemporary Art]] was one of the first to announce its closure from 14 March. Many [[Moscow]] museums announced closures in response to the mayor's ban on gatherings of 50 people or more on 17 March, and late that day the Russian culture ministry ordered the suspension of all public activities by federal and regional institutions, which resulted in many more closures from 18 March.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Spain}}. On 11 March, publicly owned museums in Madrid, including [[The Prado]], were closed indefinitely.<ref name=\":0\" /> The [[Sagrada Fam\u00edlia]] indefinitely suspended construction works and closed the monument to visitors on 13 March and the [[Guggenheim Museum Bilbao]] closed on 14 March.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Sweden}}. On 18 March, the Swedish network and cooperation organisation for public museums of national interest, ''Centralmuseernas samarbetsr\u00e5d'', recommended all their 13 members to close their public venues if the risk for transmission of the virus was assessed as high in their respective regions. Only two of them stayed open.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sverigesmuseer.se/nyheter/2020/03/cms-rekommenderar-stangning-av-centralmuseer-i-omraden-med-hog-smittspridning/|title=CMS rekommenderar st\u00e4ngning av centralmuseer i omr\u00e5den med h\u00f6g smittspridning|date=2020-03-18|website=Sveriges museer|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |UK}}. The earliest closures of cultural institutions in the UK were announced from 13 March by [[Wellcome Collection]], [[South London Gallery]], the [[Institute of Contemporary Arts]], [[The Photographers' Gallery]] and [[Amgueddfa Cymru \u2013 National Museum Wales|Amgueddfa Cymru]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/here-are-the-museums-that-have-closed-due-to-coronavirus|title=Here are the museums that have closed (so far) due to coronavirus|last=McGivern|first=Hannah|last2=Kenney|first2=Nancy|date=14 March 2020|website=The Art Newspaper|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Many other organisations announced closures on the 17 and 18 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/arts/london-museums-galleries-exhibitions-closed-coronavirus-a4389351.html|title=The London galleries and museums that are closed due to coronavirus|last=Paskett|first=Zoe|date=17 March 2020|website=Evening Standard|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-51928526|title=Tate, V&A and Natural History Museum to close|date=2020-03-17|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-GB}}</ref> The [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] closed all ticketed properties by 20 March but aimed to keep gardens and parklands open, free of chargem so that people could access the open space whilst social distancing.\n\nThe planned major exhibition at the [[National Gallery]] in London of [[Artemisia Gentileschi]], set to open on April 4, was postponed for an indeterminate time due not only to the gallery's closure but also the inability of artworks on loan from Italy and America being unable to fly during the global shutdown in air traffic.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jones|first=Jonathan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2020/mar/16/artemisia-gentileschi-national-gallery-exhibition-postponed-coronavirus|title=With coronavirus, the curse of Artemisia Gentileschi strikes again|date=2020-03-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n'''North America'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |USA}}. [[The Broadway League]] announced on March 12 that all [[Broadway theatres]] would cease performances for at least a month, even though the New York State governor had at the time allowed them to continue at 50% capacity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/12/health/broadway-coronavirus-update/index.html|title=Broadway theaters to suspend all performances because of coronavirus|author1=Taylor Romine |author2=Eric Levenson |author3=Javi Morgado|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n'''Oceania'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Australia}}. Beginning from the second week of March Australian institutions began announcing reduced services, and then complete closures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wragge.github.io/closed-glams-covid19/|title=Australian GLAMs and COVID-19|website=closed-glams-covid19|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[Opera Australia]] announced it would close on the 15th.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://operawire.com/opera-australia-cancels-performances-due-to-coronavirus/|title=Opera Australia Cancels Performances Due to Coronavirus|date=2020-03-15|website=Opera Wire|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> On the 24th the national closure of all cultural institutions was required.\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |New Zealand}}. New Zealand implemented a policy on March 23 that all institutions would be closed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ndf.org.nz/covid19-and-nz-glams|title=COVID-19 and NZ GLAMs|website=National Digital Forum|language=en-NZ|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]] closed from 6pm March 20.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Campbell|first=Georgina|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12318548|title=Coronavirus: Te Papa museum to close for two weeks|date=20 March 2020|work=New Zealand Herald|access-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Auckland War Memorial Museum]] announced that it would close from March 21.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aucklandmuseum.com/service-pages/alerts/covid-19?utm_source=wordfly&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=TemporaryMuseumClosure&utm_content=version_A|title=Auckland Museum is temporarily closed}}</ref>\n\n'''South America'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Argentina}}. All the museums, cultural activities and gatherings were cancelled in the city of Buenos Aires on the 12th of March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clarin.com/cultura/coronavirus-argentina-disponen-cierre-temporario-museos-ciudad_0_Hgfv9C32.html|title=Coronavirus en Argentina: disponen el cierre temporario de todos los museos de la Ciudad|last=|website=www.clarin.com|language=es|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> National libraries continue to offer means of contact through the main educational website of the Ministry of Education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.educ.ar/recursos/151053/bibliotecas-en-casa-en-seguimos-conectados?from=150858&fbclid=IwAR3S3KjeZavdRV6gjOCfJxVUz6Xu5L0Eqfep7SBTT5l1RrOOKvuHQDML0tY|title=#BibliotecasEnCasa en Seguimos Educando - Educ.ar|website=www.educ.ar|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Brazil}}. Museums which have closed{{when|date=March 2020}} in Brazil include the Museum of Art of S\u00e3o Paulo Assis Chateaubriand, the Pinacoteca, the Ita\u00fa Cultural, the Museum of Contemporary Art of the University of S\u00e3o Paulo, the Institute Tomie Ohtake, the Institute Moreira Salles, and the Museum of Tomorrow in Rio de Janeiro and the Instituto Inhotim contemporary art centre in Brumadinho.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Adaptations==\nFacing at least several weeks of closure of their buildings and publicly-accessible spaces, many cultural sector organisations and individual artists turned to digital activities as a way to continue fulfilling their organisational mission and obtain or retain an audience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@kajsahartig/museums-delivering-value-online-some-thoughts-during-the-covid-19-crisis-193fc0a58d22|title=Museums delivering value online \u2014 some thoughts during the Covid-19 crisis|last=Hartig|first=Kajsa|date=2020-03-29|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Farago|first=Jason|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/arts/design/coronavirus-digital-artists.html|title=The Merry-Go-Round Stopped. What Sort of Art Will Emerge?|date=2020-03-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> For example, the [[BBC]] launched a \"virtual festival of the arts\" called ''Culture in quarantine.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2020/culture-in-quarantine|title=BBC - BBC Arts announces new programmes for Culture In Quarantine - Media Centre|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Having been the first country to enforce quarantine upon its population, museums in China were also the first to provide new digital services (primarily for a domestic audience, but to a lesser extent also internationally). In January the [[National Cultural Heritage Administration]] (NCHA) said they would \"encourage cultural heritage museums and institutions around the country to utilise existing digital resources and launch online exhibitions as appropriate, providing the public with safe and convenient online services.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/travel/news/chinas-museums-offer-online-exhibitions-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/ar-BBZEOr6|title=China's museums offer online exhibitions amid coronavirus outbreak|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ncha.gov.cn/art/2020/1/28/art_722_158541.html|title=\u5173\u4e8e\u5411\"\u535a\u7269\u9986\u7f51\u4e0a\u5c55\u89c8\u5e73\u53f0\"\u63d0\u4f9b\u7f51\u4e0a\u5c55\u89c8\u5185\u5bb9\u8d44\u6e90\u7684\u5021\u8bae\u4e66|website=www.ncha.gov.cn|publisher=[[National Cultural Heritage Administration]]|language=zh|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nMany institutions turned to their existing [[social media]] presences to engage their audience online. Quickly, the [[Twitter|Twitter hashtag]] #MuseumFromHome became particularly popular for museums sharing their content in innovative ways. Various institutions were singled out for particular praise by industry analysts for their successful social media content strategy during the shutdown. These included the [[Shedd Aquarium]] in Chicago for filming their penguins visiting other animals; the [[Royal Academy]] in London for asking its followers to draw their own artworks; and the [[National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum]] in Oklahoma for providing an authentic and unusual 'voice' to their social media - from their security guard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museumnext.com/article/museum-social-media-entertains-during-the-covid-19-crisis/|title=Museum Social Media Entertains During the COVID-19 Crisis|date=2020-03-19|website=MuseumNext|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boredpanda.com/national-cowboy-museum-head-of-security-twitter/|title=Cowboy Museum Puts Their Head Of Security In Charge Of Their Twitter, And His Tweets Are Hilariously Wholesome|website=Bored Panda|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Individual actors and musicians offered [[impromptu]] performances via their personal accounts from their homes \u2013 singing [[Cover version|covers]], performing live book or [[poetry readings]], or creatively live-streaming themselves doing both normal and unusual activities.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Stubbins|first=Sinead|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2020/mar/25/coronavirus-cabin-fever-the-best-celebrities-to-follow-from-robbie-williams-to-florence-pugh|title=Coronavirus cabin fever: the best celebrities to follow, from Robbie Williams to Florence Pugh|date=2020-03-25|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n\nVarious [[internet journalism]] and [[Industry association]]s published lists of new digitally-accessible arts and culture content for their country:\n{{Expand list|date=March 2020}}\n{{columns-list|colwidth=15em|style=width: 600px;|\n*{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Argentina}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buenosaires.gob.ar/culturaencasa|title=Cultura en casa|website=Buenos Aires Ciudad - Gobierno de la Ciudad Aut\u00f3noma de Buenos Aires|language=es|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n*{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Australia}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ozglam.info/s/updates/page/welcome|title=Australian GLAM updates|website=ozglam.info|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n*{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Ireland}} <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://irishmuseums.org/text-pages/irishmuseumsonline-content-and-resources|title=#IrishMuseumsOnline: content and resources|website=Irish Museums Association|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n*{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Italy}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalist.it/arti/2020/03/13/musei-chiusi-per-coronavirus-cosa-offrono-sul-web-e-social-mentre-iorestoacasa-2054444.html|title=Musei chiusi per Coronavirus: cosa offrono sul web e social mentre #iorestoacasa|website=Globalist|language=it|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ilfattoquotidiano.it/2020/03/18/coronavirus-dal-louvre-agli-uffizi-i-musei-chiusi-ora-si-visitano-online-cineteche-teatri-e-biblioteche-cosi-la-cultura-arriva-direttamente-a-casa/5739782/|title=Coronavirus, dal Louvre agli Uffizi, i musei chiusi ora si visitano online. Cinema, teatri e biblioteche: cos\u00ec la cultura arriva direttamente a casa|date=2020-03-18|website=Il Fatto Quotidiano|language=it-IT|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n*{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |UK}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museumsassociation.org/museums-journal/news/19032020-how-digital-platforms-be-used-to-support-musems-during-covid-19-crisis|title=How can digital platforms help museums connect to audiences during Covid-19 emergency|publisher=[[Museums Association]]|website=www.museumsassociation.org|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kidsinmuseums.org.uk/2020/03/10-museum-activities-to-keep-children-entertained/|title=10 museum activities to keep children entertained|date=2020-03-23|website=Kids in Museums|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===By sector===\n====[[Public aquarium|Aquaria]] and [[zoo]]s====\nSeveral institutions launched new [[webcams]] and [[livestreams]] of their animal habitats - sometimes while animals such as penguins would be taken by [[zookeeper|keepers]] to \"visit\" other animal enclosures.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Padilla|first=Mariel|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/us/coronavirus-zoos-webcams.html|title=Stuck at Home, You Can Still Explore the Zoo or Aquarium. Some Penguins Could, Too.|date=2020-03-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-25|last2=Vigdor|first2=Neil|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/travel/story/2020-03-20/virtual-touring|title=Watching animals helps. A lot. Here are the best webcams|date=2020-03-20|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n====[[Cinema]]====\n\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema}}\n\nThe production and release schedule of many films was suspended or delayed, with some awards ceremonies and festivals being cancelled entirely. March 2020 estimates were of approximately $5b losses for the industry.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shoard|first=Catherine|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/mar/06/cinema-coronavirus-projected-5bn-loss|title=Cinema bullish in the face of coronavirus despite projected $5bn loss|date=2020-03-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Examples of adaptations included the early [[Home video|home media]] release ([[Frozen II|''Frozen II'']]), [[Theatrical release|theatrical releases]] being cancelled entirely (''[[Lost in Russia]]''), and online premieres ([[Enter the Fat Dragon (2020 film)|''Enter the Fat Dragon'']]). \n\n====[[Libraries]]====\n[[File:National_Emergency_Library.png|thumb|right|the \"National Emergency Library\" of the Internet Archive]]\nOn 24 March, the [[Internet Archive]] announced the creation of a \"National Emergency Library\", which has suspended waitlists on 1.4m ebooks from their lending library \u2013 books that are not in the public domain according to US law \u2013 in order to ensure uninterrupted access to these books for educators and students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.archive.org/2020/03/24/announcing-a-national-emergency-library-to-provide-digitized-books-to-students-and-the-public/|title=Announcing a National Emergency Library to Provide Digitized Books to Students and the Public|last=|first=|date=24 March 2020|website=Internet Archive Blogs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2020/03/internet-archive-offers-thousands-of-copyrighted-books-for-free-online/|title=Internet Archive offers 1.4 million copyrighted books for free online|last=Lee|first=Timothy B.|date=2020-03-28|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Similarly, the [[National library of Israel]] announced it would be offering free audiobooks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/israel-news/national-library-offers-free-audiobooks-amid-coronavirus-closures-621664|title=National Library offers free audiobooks amid coronavirus closures|website=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> The Library of the [[National Congress of Argentina]] created activities including public readings and delivery of selected artworks through [[Instagram]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/cultura/2020/03/18/biblioteca-del-congreso-todas-las-actividades-online-durante-la-pandemia-del-coronavirus/|title=Biblioteca del Congreso: todas las actividades online durante la pandemia del coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=Infobae|language=es-ES|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n====[[Museums]]====\n{{Quote box\n|width     = 22em\n|border    = 1px\n|align     = right\n|fontsize  = 100%\n|salign    = center\n|quote     =\n\u201cThis year, the paint has more time to dry.\u201d<br> \nA statement from the [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]] announcing a delay to the [[Archibald Prize]] portraiture exhibition until after the health crisis, \"when art will be needed more than ever\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/art-and-design/paint-has-more-time-to-dry-archibald-prize-delayed-20200321-p54ck2.html|title='Paint has more time to dry': Archibald Prize delayed|date=21 March 2020|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n}}\n\nMany websites were rapidly updated to focus on digital resources. In mid-March the [[Museum Computer Network]] published an extensive \"Guide to Virtual Museum Resources, E-Learning, and Online Collections\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mcn.edu/a-guide-to-virtual-museum-resources/|title=The Ultimate Guide to Virtual Museum Resources|date=2020-03-15|website=MCN|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Lists also were published of fine-art museums with existing interactive services (notably those already \"partners\" of [[Google Arts & Culture]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/547919/2500-virtual-museum-tours-google-arts-culture/|title=2,500 Museums You Can Now Visit Virtually|date=2020-03-16|website=Hyperallergic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Philbrook Museum of Art]]'s rapid relaunch their website in late-March \u2013 in order \"for us all to spend some time practicing social distancing and experiencing the #MuseumFromHome\" \u2013 was described as a model example of how an institution could \"Reorganise, Reuse and Rethink\" its activities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museumnext.com/article/reorganise-reuse-get-creative-and-relaunch-lessons-from-philbrook/|title=Reorganise, Reuse, Rethink and Relaunch - Lessons from Philbrook|date=2020-03-21|website=MuseumNext|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Other specific examples included [[Europeana]] publishing a digital gallery of images relating to the theme of [[handwashing]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.europeana.eu/en/galleries/washing-your-hands|title=Washing your hands|website=www.europeana.eu|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> and the [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|Museum of New Zealand]] publishing a \"little page of calm\" (a reference to the 1997 bestselling book ''[[Little book of calm]]'').<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tepapa.govt.nz/discover-collections/read-watch-play/little-page-calm|title=The little page of calm|date=2020-03-16|website=Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa, Wellington, NZ|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n====[[Music]]====\nIndividually and collectively, [[musicians]] organised online performances, often via their own social media platforms. Some were especially planned and prepared; some were impromptu. For example, cellist [[Yo-Yo Ma|YoYo Ma]] used his social media account \"#songsofcomfort\" as a way to share music. His first offering was \"Going Home\" by [[Anton\u00edn Dvo\u0159\u00e1k|Antonin Dvo\u0159\u00e1k.]] Inspired by his example, others followed suit with their own at-home performances. The West Australian Symphony Orchestra renamed themselves the \"West Australian Social Distancing Orchestra\" and played a re-arranged version of ''[[Bol\u00e9ro]]'' by [[Maurice Ravel|Maurice Ravel. T]]<nowiki/>he quickly organised \"Instagram Live Music Festival\"''Isol Aid'' (a reference to [[Live Aid]]) of 72 Australian bands was broadcast on the weekend of 21\u201322 March. Each artist performed from wherever the were [[Isolation (health care)|self isolating]] and \"... play a 20-minute set streamed live on their Instagram accounts, and then tag-team the next artist to play\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/isol-aid-instagram-live-music-festival-coronavirus-covid-19/12072202|title=Isol-Aid is a stacked Aussie livestreaming music festival that's happening this weekend|last=Newstead|first=Al|date=2020-03-19|website=triple j|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://linktr.ee/isolaidfestival|title=@isolaidfestival|website=Linktree|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> while one amateur choir gathered the contributions of more than 1000 people from 18 countries to create a video performance of \u201cClose To You\u201d by [[The Carpenters]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HezxInuN1YA|title=Couch Choir - (They Long To Be) Close To You|last=|first=|date=22 March 2020|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In the middle of March, [[Bob Dylan]] released a single 17 minute new song called \"[[Murder Most Foul (song)|Murder Most Foul]]\", his first piece of original material in eight years.<ref>{{Cite news|last=McFadyen|first=Matthew|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/murder-most-foul-bob-dylan-s-surprise-song-for-the-viral-age-20200330-p54f8z.html|title=Murder Most Foul: Bob Dylan's surprise song for the viral age|date=30 March 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\nOther musicians, singers and songwriters adapted to the crisis by turning to teaching online.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lamond|first=Scott|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-26/coronavirus-cant-stop-the-music-as-online-lessons-in-demand/12089060|title=Coronavirus sees ARIA-winning musicians turn online teachers as students flock to lessons|date=26 March 2020|work=ABC News|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSeveral musical artists delayed the releases of albums due to the pandemic.<ref name=\"rstone1\">{{cite web |last1=Leight |first1=Elias |title=They Were Going to Be Spring's Biggest Albums -- Until COVID-19 Hit |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/album-delays-caused-by-covid-19-973870/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=30 March 2020}}</ref> [[Record Store Day]] was rescheduled from April 18 to June 20.<ref>{{cite web |title=Record Store Day 2020 Postponed Due to Coronavirus Concerns |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/record-store-day-2020-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-concerns/ |website=Pitchfork |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe following is a list of albums whose release dates have been rescheduled as the result of the coronavirus pandemic:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Artist\n!Album Title\n!Original date\n!Rescheduled date\n!Source\n|-\n|{{hs|1975, The}}[[The 1975]]\n|''[[Notes on a Conditional Form]]''\n|April 24\n|May 22\n|<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shaffer |first1=Claire |title=The 1975 Postpone 'Notes on a Conditional Form' Release Date (Again) |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-1975-notes-on-a-conditional-form-delayed-975183/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Biffy Clyro]]\n|''[[A Celebration of Endings]]''\n|May 15\n|August 14\n|<ref name=\"spin1\"/>\n|-\n|[[DMA's]]\n|''The Glow''\n|April 24\n|July 10\n|<ref name=\"spin1\"/>\n|-\n|[[Jarvis Cocker|Jarv Is]]\n|''[[Beyond the Pale (Jarv Is album)|Beyond the Pale]]''\n|May 1\n|September 4\n|<ref name=\"spin1\"/>\n|-\n|{{hs|Gallagher, Liam}}[[Liam Gallagher]]\n|''MTV Unplugged''\n|April 24\n|TBA\n|<ref name=\"spin1\"/>\n|-\n|[[Haim (band)|Haim]]\n|''[[Women in Music Pt. III|Women in Music Pt. III]]''\n|April 24\n|Summer 2020\n|<ref name=\"spin1\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Here Are the Album Release Dates That Have Changed |url=https://www.spin.com/2020/03/coronavirus-here-are-the-album-release-dates-that-have-changed/ |website=Spin |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Hinds (band)|Hinds]]\n|''[[The Prettiest Curse]]''\n|April 3\n|June 5\n|<ref name=\"spin1\"/>\n|-\n|{{hs|Keys, Alicia}}[[Alicia Keys]]\n|''[[Alicia (album)|Alicia]]''\n|March 20\n|May 15\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=A list of albums delayed due to coronavirus (Updated) |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/a-list-of-albums-delayed-due-to-coronavirus__29162/ |website=www.officialcharts.com |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Lady Gaga]]\n|''[[Chromatica]]''\n|March 25\n|TBA\n|<ref name=\"spin1\"/>\n|-\n|{{hs|Lemon Twigs, The}}[[The Lemon Twigs]]\n|''Songs for the General Public''\n|May 1\n|August 21\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=The Lemon Twigs\u2019 new album has been delayed because of the coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.thelineofbestfit.com/news/latest-news/the-lemon-twigs-new-album-delayed-because-of-coronavirus-pandemic |website=The Line of Best Fit |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{hs|McKenna, Declan}}[[Declan McKenna]]\n|''Zeros''\n|May 15\n|August 21\n|<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clarke |first1=Patrick |title=Declan McKenna delays the release of new album \u2018Zeros\u2019 and cancels tour due to coronavirus crisis |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/declan-mckenna-delays-the-release-of-new-album-zeros-and-cancels-tour-due-to-coronavirus-crisis-2634304 |website=NME |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{hs|Nelson, Willie}}[[Willie Nelson]]\n|''[[First Rose of Spring]]''\n|April 24\n|July 3\n|<ref name=\"spin1\"/>\n|-\n|{{hs|Pretenders, The}}[[The Pretenders]]\n|''Hate for Sale''\n|May 1\n|July 17\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=The Pretenders Announce New Album Hate for Sale, Share \"The Buzz\": Stream |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/03/the-pretenders-hate-for-sale-the-buzz-stream/ |website=Consequence of Sound |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{hs|Price, Margo}}[[Margo Price]]\n|''[[That's How Rumors Get Started]]''\n|May 8\n|Summer 2020\n|<ref name=\"spin1\"/>\n|-\n|{{hs|Smith, Sam}}[[Sam Smith]]\n|[[Upcoming Sam Smith album|Currently untitled]]\n|May 1\n|TBA\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=Sam Smith Pushing Back and Changing Title of New Album |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/sam-smith-pushing-back-and-changing-title-of-new-album/ |website=Pitchfork |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\nIn contrast to the postponements, some musical acts, such as [[Dua Lipa]] and [[Sufjan Stevens]], moved up the release dates of their upcoming albums.<ref name=\"sgum1\">{{cite web |last1=Rettig |first1=James |title=HAIM, Dua Lipa, Willie Nelson, & Sufjan Stevens Among Artists Moving Album Release Dates Amid Pandemic |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2077667/dua-lipa-willie-nelson-sufjan-stevens-among-artists-moving-album-release-dates-amid-pandemic/news/ |website=Stereogum |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Others, such as [[Nine Inch Nails]] and [[Phish]], released new albums with little or no notice.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Farokhmanesh |first1=Megan |title=Nine Inch Nails just released two new albums for free |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/26/21195266/nine-inch-nails-new-albums-just-ghosts-v-vi-free-download |website=The Verge |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kreps |first1=Daniel |title=Phish to Debut New Album 'Sigma Oasis' During April 1st Livestream |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/phish-new-album-sigma-oasis-976437/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====[[Performing arts]]====\nNew (or a newly expanded range) free [[online streaming]] of previously recorded theatrical performances was provided by many institutions.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Convery|first=Stephanie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2020/mar/20/livestreaming-schedule-music-art-literature-and-events-from-australia-and-beyond|title=Livestreaming schedule: music, art, literature and events from Australia and beyond|date=2020-03-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-26|last2=Rawson|first2=Sharnee|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> For example, the [[Metropolitan Opera]] of New York broadcast a new opera each evening, including an entire [[Ring Cycle]] performed during the 2010\u201312 seasons, via their own app,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/in-wake-of-season-cancellation-metropolitan-opera-continues-free-streaming-series-with-a-week-of-wagner|title=In Wake of Season Cancellation, Metropolitan Opera Continues Free Streaming Series With a Week of Wagner|last=McPhee|first=Ryan|date=2020-03-23|website=[[Playbill]]|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> and the [[Bolshoi Ballet]] company of Moscow made available six of their recorded performances via [[YouTube]] for 24 hours each.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2020/03/27/spend-an-evening-at-the-bolshoi-a69775|title=Spend an Evening at the Bolshoi|last=|first=|date=2020-03-27|website=The Moscow Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-russia-bolshoi-idUSKBN21E35D|title=Russia's Bolshoi Theater goes online as coronavirus curbs public life|date=2020-03-27|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-29|language=en}}</ref> The [[West End theatre|West End]] production of ''[[The Wind in the Willows (musical)|The Wind in the Willows]]'' was also streamed for UK residents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://londonist.com/london/theatre-and-arts/wind-in-the-willows-streaming-west-end|title=You Can Screen The West End's Wind In The Willows Online For Free|date=2020-03-18|website=Londonist|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nIndividual actors of the first rank, such as [[Patrick Stewart]] and [[Sam Neill]] used their skill from isolation to entertain, support and get out the message that \"we really need to be in this together and that this has to take the form of being apart\" as Neill described his singing and reciting. His contribution was described as a skilled actor \"pretending to be an ordinary joe amusing himself beyond his capacity\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Craven|first=Peter|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/movies/when-the-going-got-tough-sam-neill-got-out-his-ukulele-20200330-p54fd8.html|title=When the going got tough, Sam Neill got out his ukulele|date=1 April 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Stewart, a trained Shakespearian actor with a \"deep velvety\" voice, broadcast himself reading one [[Shakespearean sonnet]] each day via [[Instagram]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://londonist.com/london/books-and-poetry/patrick-stewart-is-treating-twitter-to-one-shakespearan-sonnet-a-day-during-lockdown|title=Patrick Stewart Is Treating Twitter To One Shakespeare Sonnet A Day During Lockdown|date=2020-03-25|website=Londonist|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>  \n\n==Impacts==\n===Budgets and employment===\n{{see also|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nDue to the closures, revenues for cultural organisations reliant on ticket sales were expected to cause devastating effects upon revenues, with consequent impacts upon organisational staffing, and on independent artists and professionals. This is due to the fact that the arts and culture is a sector of national economies characterised by particularly a high proportion of self-employment.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/arts-council-england-emergency-relief-fund-1814829|title=Arts Council England Has Launched a $190 Million Emergency Relief Package for Creative Organizations and Artists|date=2020-03-25|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> For example, by the 20th of March the [[Cirque du Soleil]] had [[laid off]] 95% of its workforce and closed [[traveling circus]] performances operating in seven countries,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/cirque-de-soleil-canada-coronavirus-staff-fired-1493386|title=Cirque du Soleil lays off 95 percent of its workforce after coronavirus forces closure of all its shows globally|last=Cole|first=Brendan|date=2020-03-20|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> The world commercial art market declined 5% in 2019 compared to the previous year, and is expected to decline further in 2020 \u2013 with 6 of the world's 10 largest auction houses operating exclusively in China. Major art fairs such as [[Hong Kong Arts Festival]] and [[Art Basel]] were cancelled, furthering a shift towards online purchases and the creation of VIP \"online viewing rooms\" rather than physical displaying at [[art auctions]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/the-coronavirus-pandemic-corona-panic-is-shaking-up-worlds-global-art-market-starting-in-hong-kong/a-52651815|title=The coronavirus is shaking up the world's art market in unexpected ways|publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]]|website=DW.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nArts and culture sector budgetary and employment reports from individual countries included:<br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Australia}}. [[Opera Australia]] \u2013 the nation's largest [[performing arts]] company \u2013 temporarily stood down nearly all its staff<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/exit-stage-left-opera-australia-leads-arts-shutdown-20200325-p54dq1|title=Exit stage left: Opera Australia leads arts shutdown|date=2020-03-26|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> amid speculation it would also need to sell major assets in order to avoid [[bankruptcy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/opera-australia-looks-to-sell-offs-to-stay-afloat-20200316-p54ai2.html|title=Opera Australia looks to sell-offs to stay afloat|last=Galvin|first=Nick|date=2020-03-16|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> By the 23rd of March, 255,000 cultural events had been cancelled with an estimated revenue loss of $A280 million, self reported through the crowdsourced website ILostMyGig.net.au.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/coronavirus-what-the-latest-stimulus-measures-mean-for-australian-artists-and-arts-organisations-134233|title=Coronavirus: what the latest stimulus measures mean for Australian artists and arts organisations|last=Caust|first=Jo|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Italy}}. In March, when many institutions closed for the first time since [[WWII]], the state-funded museum sector had been valued at \u20ac27 billion or 1.6% of national GDP \u2013 slightly smaller than the agriculture sector.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/coronavirus-l-impatto-negativo-chiusure-musei-che-valgono-l-16percento-pil-AC4pFCMB|title=Coronavirus, l'impatto negativo delle chiusure sui musei (che valgono l'1,6% del Pil)|website=Il Sole 24 ORE|language=it|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |USA}}. As the pandemic spread and closures became the standard not the exception, institutions started publishing expected revenue shortfall calculations, began to fire staff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AMTransparency/status/1242869675425443840|title=This will be a thread for tracking museum layoff news.|date=2020-03-25|website=Twitter|publisher=Art + Museum Transparency|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> For example: the [[Metropolitan opera]] expects to lose $60m in revenue;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Woolfe|first=Zachary|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/19/arts/music/metropolitan-opera-coronavirus.html|title=Metropolitan Opera Cancels Season Over Virus and Faces $60 Million Loss|date=2020-03-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> the [[Metropolitan Museum]] expects to lose $100m in revenue with likely layoffs;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Pogrebin|first=Robin|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/arts/design/met-museum-coronavirus-closure.html|title=Met Museum Prepares for $100 Million Loss and Closure Till July|date=2020-03-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and SFMOMA [[furlough]]ed 300 staff in the expectation of a 40% decrease in revenue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/arts/13877653/sfmoma-to-lay-off-or-furlough-over-300-museum-staff|title=SFMOMA to Lay Off or Furlough Over 300 Museum Staff|last=Hotchkiss|first=Sarah|date=2020-03-27|website=[[KQED]]|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The [[Science Museum of Minnesota]] expected to lose $15m in revenue over three months. Consequently, it \"temporarily\" [[laid off]] most of its staff in an announcement via a [[Google Hangouts]] videocall in late March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.startribune.com/minnesota-science-museum-children-s-museum-lay-off-most-staff-in-wake-of-covid-19-outbreak/569063662/|title=Science Museum of Minnesota, Children's Museum temporarily lay off most staff in wake of COVID-19|website=Star Tribune|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Meanwhile, staff across the museum began to unionise, even though \"[[Social distancing]] orders prevent the in-person meetings required to sign the cards required to file for union elections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tinyletter.com/artandmuseumtransparency/letters/art-museum-transparency-newsletter-2-march-2020|title=Art + Museum Transparency Newsletter #2 -- March 2020|last=|first=|date=2020-03-26|website=artandmuseumtransparency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Financial stimulus ===\nWith the extensive financial disruption across all areas of the economy, many governments announced [[Stimulus (economics)|fiscal stimulus]] and [[Bailout|economic bailout]] packages which included specific resources for the arts and cultural sectors. Equally, various [[charities]] and industry bodies raised funds to support their sector.\n\nArts and culture sector financial stimulus packages from individual countries included:\n{{Expand list|date=March 2020}}\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Australia}}. petition of over 50 arts and culture organisations (including peak bodies from the music, dance, visual arts, museums, writers' and indigenous arts groups) requested a financial aid package \"...to a value of 2% of the $111.7 billion [cultural and creative] industry\" and requesting the Prime Minister \"...issue a public statement recognising the value of our industry to all Australians\" and noting that the industry had not yet recovered from the impact of the [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://visualarts.net.au/news-opinion/2020/creative-industry-unites/|title=Creative industry unites to secure Australia's cultural life|website=NAVA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Germany}}. The minister for culture [[Monika Gr\u00fctters]] declared that \"artists are not only indispensable, but also vital, especially now.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/german-bailout-50-billion-1815396|title=Germany Has Rolled Out a Staggering \u20ac50 Billion Aid Package For Small Businesses That Boosts Artists and Galleries\u2014and Puts Other Countries to Shame|date=2020-03-25|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The statement was made while announcing a \u20ac50 billion stimulus package for small business and freelancers \u2013 explicitly including the creative sectors.\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Sweden}}. The Swedish Minister of Culture [[Amanda Lind]] presented a 1 billion [[Swedish krona|SEK]] support package for sports and culture, where 500 million SEK was earmarked for culture (not including government agencies like the [[Royal Dramatic Theatre]] and [[Kungliga Operan]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=En miljard i akut st\u00f6d till kultur och idrott|url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/coronaviruset/en-miljard-i-akut-stod-till-kultur-och-idrott/|publisher=Expressen|access-date=2020-03-25|language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |UK}}. [[The Film and TV Charity]] created an emergency relief fund in order to \"provide emergency short-term relief to active workers and freelancers who have been directly affected by the closure of productions across the UK\", with an initial donation of \u00a31m from [[Netflix]] and by \u00a3500,000 from the [[BBC]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/bfi-uk-film-and-tv-charity-set-up-covid-19-emergency-relief-fund-with-1m-donation-from-netflix-1202890966/|title=BFI & UK Film And TV Charity Set Up Covid-19 Emergency Relief Fund With \u00a31M Donation From Netflix|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=2020-03-24|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/bbc-donates-to-covid-19-emergency-relief-fund-1202894127/|title=BBC Joins Netflix In Making $600,000 Donation To Coronavirus Emergency Relief Fund|last=Kanter|first=Jake|date=2020-03-27|website=Deadline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The [[Museums Association]] called upon the UK government to divert \u00a3120m that was intended for the [[Festival of Britain 2022]] to bail out museums in financial distress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museumsassociation.org/museums-journal/news/17032020-museum-closures-coronavirus-covid-19|title=Museums and galleries close as coronavirus emergency intensifies|last=Kendall Adams|first=Geraldine|date=17 March 2020|website=Museums Association|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" /> [[Arts Council England]] announced \u00a3160 million would be made available for arts organisations, including \u00a350 million for organisations it does not usually fund and \u00a320 million for individual and freelance artists.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |USA}}. A petition was begun by the [[American Alliance of Museums]] to request that the museum sector was included in any future [[economic stimulus]] from the United States government,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congressweb.com/AAM/67|title=Tell Congress: Include Museums in COVID-19 Economic Relief|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> while the Metropolitan museum was more specific \u2013 requesting $4 billion for at-risk museums.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/metropolitan-museum-of-art-congress-1813665|title=The Metropolitan Museum of Art Is Calling on the US Government to Bail Out At-Risk Museums With $4 Billion in Aid|date=2020-03-24|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nIn late March the United States federal government announced a $2 trillion economic stimulus package. It included: \"$75 million for the [[National Endowment for the Arts]] and $75 million for the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]], which can pass on the money to institutions that need it. Another $50 million was designated to the [[Institute of Museum and Library Services]], which distributes funds to museums and libraries.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Jacobs|first=Julia|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/24/arts/coronavirus-arts-bailout.html|title=Arts Groups, Facing Their Own Virus Crisis, Get a Piece of the Stimulus|date=2020-03-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> While a common argument in the USA against the cultural sector receiving stimulus funding was that \"Arts groups may be 'nice,' but they\u2019re far from 'necessary.'\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Copyright ===\nAcademic librarians in the United States made public statements on the applicability and importance of the role of the [[fair use]] copyright exception for \"Emergency Remote Teaching & Research\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/document/d/10baTITJbFRh7D6dHVVvfgiGP2zqaMvm0EHHZYf2cBRk/mobilebasic?urp=gmail_link|title=Public Statement: Fair Use & Emergency Remote Teaching & Research|website=docs.google.com|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[Cornell University Library]] made the advice explicit, noting in a new official library policy recommending, \"...that faculty may scan course material in amounts that may exceed customary fair use limits under normal circumstances. Fair use provides flexibility to permit faculty scan broader amounts of course material than normal during these exigent circumstances.\" and noted that library staff were no longer allowed to work on-site and therefore not able to scan materials on behalf of teaching staff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://copyright.cornell.edu/covid|title=COVID-19 & Copyright at Cornell {{!}} Copyright Information Center|website=copyright.cornell.edu|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nThe libraries of universities and of the [[National Research Council (Italy)|National Research Council]] in Italy petitioned [[academic publishers]] to provide temporary [[open access]] to publications in order to medical staff, scientific researchers, and the general public access during the national emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.centumcellae.it/cronaca/appello-per-il-diritto-di-accesso-alla-conoscenza-scientifica-in-stato-di-emergenza/|title=APPELLO PER IL DIRITTO DI ACCESSO ALLA CONOSCENZA SCIENTIFICA IN STATO DI EMERGENZA|last=|first=|date=2020-03-19|website=Centumcellae|language=it-IT|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n[[LeVar Burton]], host of [[Reading Rainbow]], announced his desire to perform live-streamed readings of books for his podcast ''LeVar Reads'' but that copyright law was unclear as to whether this was allowed. [[Neil Gaiman]] replied by twitter giving permission to read any of his works.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/939vjv/please-dont-sue-levar-burton-for-reading-soothing-stories-to-scared-children|title=Please Don't Sue LeVar Burton for Reading Soothing Stories to Scared Children|last=Cole|first=Samantha|date=2020-03-26|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nVarious online training workshops were organised for cultural heritage to learn about relevant risks and [[Copyright exceptions|exceptions to copyright]] when providing online services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/open-glam/copyright-open-access-for-glams-in-the-age-of-covid-19-1213b67a0e21|title=Copyright & Open Access for GLAMs in the age of COVID-19|date=2020-03-24|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Equally, [[digital strategy]] workshops<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usingdata.com/usingdata/2020/3/19/free-strategy-workshops-march-23-april-3|title=Free strategy workshops March 23 \u2013 April 3|website=Usingdata|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> and live Q&A sessions with experts were organised.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AAMers/status/1242798776655413249|title=What #COVID19 questions do you want to pose to the museum field? Comment below or DM us to include it in our #MuseumsDiscussCOVID19 Tweet chat! TODAY 3-4 pm|publisher=American Alliance of Museums|date=2020-03-25|website=Twitter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n=== New cultural works ===\n\nWith thorough and global disruption society to an unprecedented level, there is the expectation of many and diverse cultural works created which reference or are inspired by the pandemic and its effects. One gallery director said: \"There will definitely be an explosion in new material.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dye|first=Josh|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/art-and-design/perplexing-and-confusing-art-gallery-of-nsw-director-grapples-with-coronavirus-crisis-20200327-p54emd.html|title='Perplexing and confusing': Art Gallery of NSW director grapples with coronavirus crisis|date=28 March 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>{{Expand list|date=March 2020}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema]]\n* [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the arts and cultural heritage}}\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|arts]]\n[[Category:2020 in arts]]\n[[Category:Cultural heritage]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{current related||2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Globalize|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n[[File:Closed library - Island Bay.jpg|alt=|thumb|300x300px|Announcement posted in the door of a [[public library]] in [[Island Bay, New Zealand]] that it is closed due to the pandemic, and will waive all [[Late fees|late return fees]].]]\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] had a substantial impact on the [[performing arts]] and cultural heritage ([[GLAM (industry sector)|GLAM]]) sectors. The global health crisis and the uncertainly resulting from it profoundly affected organisations' operations as well as individuals \u2013 both employed and independent \u2013 across the sector. Arts and culture sector organisations attempted to uphold their (often publicly funded) mission to provide access to cultural heritage to the community, maintain the safety of their employees and the public, and support artists where possible.\n\nBy March 2020, across the world and to varying degrees, museums, performance venues, and other cultural institutions had been indefinitely closed with their exhibitions, events and performances cancelled or postponed. In response there were intensive efforts to provide alternative services through digital platforms, and an awareness that there would be much new cultural work being produced which had been inspired by the events.\n\nMany individuals across the sector would temporarily or permanently lose contracts or employment with varying degrees of warning and financial assistance available, equally, financial stimulus from governments, and charities for artists, would provide greatly differing levels of support depending on the sector and the country.\n\n==Closures== \nThrough the first months of 2020, arts and culture sector organisations around the world progressively restricted their public activities and closed completely due to the coronavirus pandemic. Starting with China, and East-Asia, by mid-to-late March most organisations worldwide had either closed voluntarily or by government mandate. This included museums,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/here-are-the-museums-that-have-closed-due-to-coronavirus|title=Here are the museums that have closed (so far) due to coronavirus|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artnews.com/art-news/news/coronavirus-museum-closures-worldwide-1202680933/|title=See a List of Coronavirus-Related Closures at Museums Around the World|last=Solomon|first=Claire Selvin,Tessa|last2=Selvin|first2=Claire|date=2020-03-12|website=ARTnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26|last3=Solomon|first3=Tessa}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/document/d/1LNCETkPjgcNdmybrwE5g2JEK4KpIfhKThnws1QqgjqE/mobilebasic|title=Museum Responses - COVID-19|website=docs.google.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> theatre and stage productions,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2020/mar/13/coronavirus-culture-arts-films-gigs-festivals-cancellations|title=Coronavirus and culture \u2013 a list of major cancellations|date=2020-03-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-26|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and arts festivals.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/here-are-the-museums-that-have-closed-due-to-coronavirus|title=Here are the museums that have closed (so far) due to coronavirus|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 2020, dates for re-opening and expectations for when cultural organisation can fully \"return to normal\" are unknown for most of the world. Survey data from March in the USA indicated that, when museums were permitted to reopen, the public \"intent to visit\" metric for cultural activities should be unchanged overall from prior to the pandemic \u2013 but with a shifted preference for the ''kind'' of activity. Data indicated there would be a decreased willingness for attendance of activities in confined spaces, large immobile groups (such as cinemas), or tactile activities; with an increase in interest for activities outdoors or with large spaces (such as zoos and botanic gardens).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.colleendilen.com/2020/03/25/how-is-covid-19-impacting-likelihood-to-attend-different-cultural-entities-data/|title=Post-Pandemic, Which Cultural Entity Types Are People More Likely to Revisit? (DATA)|date=2020-03-25|website=Colleen Dilenschneider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.colleendilen.com/2020/03/23/weekly-data-update-how-covid-19-is-impacting-intentions-to-visit-cultural-entities-march-23-2020/|title=DATA UPDATE: How COVID-19 is Impacting Intentions to Visit Cultural Entities - March 23, 2020|date=2020-03-23|website=Colleen Dilenschneider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n''The following is a list of notable closures, announcements and policies affecting the cultural sector.<br>For comprehensive lists:''\n{{See also|List of public venues and institutions closed during the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic}} \n{{See also|List of events affected by the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n'''Africa'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Egypt}}. From March 23 until March 31, 2020 all museums and archaeological sites in Egypt were closed to the public for sterilization and disinfection. During this period a programme to raise the awareness of the sites and museums\u2019 employees on ways of prevention and protection against the virus took place.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cairoscene.com/Buzz/Egypt-to-Close-All-Museums-and-Archaeological-Sites|title= Egypt to close all museums and archaeological sites}}</ref>\n\n'''Asia'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |China}}. On 23 January 2020 all museums were closed throughout mainland China, As the first country for the virus to spread, China was also the first to close its GLAMs.<ref name=\":0\" /> By Mid-March Chinese institutions had slowly and cautiously begun to allow various public activities to be restored with the [[Shanghai Museum]] and the [[Power Station of Art]] (also in Shanghai) reopening on the 13th. Both had restricted visitor numbers and the latter noted that, \u201cWe have also prepared a temporary quarantine area on every floor in case of any emergencies. All visitors must have their temperature taken, as well as present their ID card and registered health code, before entering.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artnews.com/art-news/news/china-japan-south-korea-museums-reopen-coronavirus-1202680994/|title=Museums in China, South Korea, Japan Begin to Reopen After Coronavirus Lockdown|last=Solomon|first=Tessa|last2=Solomon|first2=Tessa|date=2020-03-13|website=ARTnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Some other private galleries in China had begun to open, as had some institutions in South Korea and Japan with limited service (such as by private tour only). By the end of the month 40% of mainland China's tourism attractions had reopened yet most art venues remained closed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/china-south-korea-and-japan-start-to-reopen-museums|title=China, South Korea and Japan start to reopen museums after strict coronavirus lockdown|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n:{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Hong Kong}}. Following the mainland, Hong Kong closed its museums five days later.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Japan}}. On 28 February Japan announced all museums would be closed \"until 17 March\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in|Qatar}}. Qatar museums run by the state closed on 12 March. A forthcoming collaborative show on Picasso's Studio's due to be held by the [[Fire Station (gallery)|Fire Station]] and [[Mus\u00e9e Picasso]] has been indefinitely postponed.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |South Korea}}. On 23 February, one month after mainland China, South Korea closed all museums \"until further notice\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n'''Europe'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts -->\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Austria}}. All federal public museums were closed by directors in response to government precautionary measures banning large events and arrivals from Italy. The [[Albertina Modern]] museum was supposed to open on 13 March but this opening was indefinitely postponed.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Belgium}}. All cultural activities regardless of size were banned by the government from 14 March, which involved the closure of the [[Jan van Eyck]] exhibition at the [[Museum of Fine Arts, Ghent]].<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |France}}. Weeks earlier than French government regulations required it, staff of [[The Louvre]] \"almost unanimously\" voted to force the closure of the museum on the 1st of March, due to concerns for their own health.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51697644|title=Staff force Louvre closure over coronavirus fears|date=2020-03-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> It closed for three days, reopened,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Coronavirus: Louvre museum in Paris reopens after staff walkout|url=https://www.thelocal.fr/20200301/frances-louvre-museum-closed-due-to-virus-fears|website=www.thelocal.fr|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> accepted only visitors with pre-booked tickets from the 9th,<ref name=\":0\" /> then closed definitively on the 13th by government mandate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200313-france-s-louvre-museum-and-versailles-palace-to-shut-over-coronavirus-crisis|title=Louvre, Versailles and Eiffel Tower close over coronavirus crisis|date=2020-03-13|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Reconstruction of the [[Notre-Dame de Paris|Notre-Dame cathedral]] following [[Notre-Dame de Paris fire|the 2019 fire]] was also halted because of worker security.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Germany}}. On 16 March 2020, the German chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] announced in a press conference that the government and [[minister-president]]s had together agreed upon guidelines to limit social contacts in public spaces. Theatres, opera houses, concert halls, museums, exhibition spaces, cinemas, amusement parks and zoos needed to close.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bundesregierung.de/breg-de/themen/coronavirus/leitlinien-bund-laender-1731000|title=Leitlinien gegen Ausbreitung des Coronavirus|date=2020-03-16|website=Die Bundesregierung|language=de|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Italy}}. As the the worst hit country in Europe during February and March, national closures were announced on the 23rd of February with an initial reopening date of 1 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/la-cultura-chiusa-tempi-coronavirus-ACNKCpLB|title=La cultura chiusa ai tempi del coronavirus|website=Il Sole 24 ORE|language=it|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Museums outside the \"red zone\" of highly infected areas in the North were then permitted to re-open as long as visitors stayed 1 meter apart,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/italian-museums-reopen-following-government-green-light|title=Coronavirus: Louvre closes while Italian museums reopen following government green light|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> this was later rescinded and all institution were closed until at least 3 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/rome-s-blockbuster-raphael-exhibition-closes|title=Coronavirus in Italy: Ai Weiwei criticised for 'insensitive' pasta meme and Raphael blockbuster closes|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Netherlands}}. On 12 March, Amsterdam's [[Rijksmuseum]] and [[Van Gogh Museum]] announced they would close until at least the end of that month.<ref name=\":0\" /> The following day, having previously announced the reading room and exhibition would remain open, the [[Nationaal Archief|National Archives]] announced their complete closure until April 6.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationaalarchief.nl/beleven/nieuws/studiezaal-en-tentoonstelling-nationaal-archief-tijdelijk-gesloten|title=Studiezaal en tentoonstelling Nationaal Archief tijdelijk gesloten|website=Nationaal Archief|language=nl|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>  On 30 March, the painting ''[[The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen]]'' (1884) by [[Vincent van Gogh]] was stolen from the [[Singer Laren|Singer Laren museum]] while the museum was closed.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/europe/i-m-absolutely-livid-van-gogh-painting-stolen-from-museum-during-pandemic-20200331-p54fgd.html|title='I'm absolutely livid': Van Gogh painting stolen from museum during pandemic|date=31 March 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Poland}}. On 11 March a regional government \"recommendation\" was made that all cultural venues in the [[Tricity, Poland|tricity]] area be closed for two weeks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kultura.trojmiasto.pl/Teatry-odwolane-imprezy-spektakle-koronawirus-w-Trojmiescie-n143084.html|title=Teatry zamkni\u0119te przynajmniej na 2 tygodnie|date=2020-03-10|website=trojmiasto.pl|language=pl|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Museums, including the [[Auschwitz-Birkenau State Museum]], and other cultural venues such as theatres and cinemas were then closed by the national government with an initial re-opening date of 25 March.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Russia}}. The [[Garage Museum of Contemporary Art]] was one of the first to announce its closure from 14 March. Many [[Moscow]] museums announced closures in response to the mayor's ban on gatherings of 50 people or more on 17 March, and late that day the Russian culture ministry ordered the suspension of all public activities by federal and regional institutions, which resulted in many more closures from 18 March.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Spain}}. On 11 March, publicly owned museums in Madrid, including [[The Prado]], were closed indefinitely.<ref name=\":0\" /> The [[Sagrada Fam\u00edlia]] indefinitely suspended construction works and closed the monument to visitors on 13 March and the [[Guggenheim Museum Bilbao]] closed on 14 March.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Sweden}}. On 18 March, the Swedish network and cooperation organisation for public museums of national interest, ''Centralmuseernas samarbetsr\u00e5d'', recommended all their 13 members to close their public venues if the risk for transmission of the virus was assessed as high in their respective regions. Only two of them stayed open.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sverigesmuseer.se/nyheter/2020/03/cms-rekommenderar-stangning-av-centralmuseer-i-omraden-med-hog-smittspridning/|title=CMS rekommenderar st\u00e4ngning av centralmuseer i omr\u00e5den med h\u00f6g smittspridning|date=2020-03-18|website=Sveriges museer|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |UK}}. The earliest closures of cultural institutions in the UK were announced from 13 March by [[Wellcome Collection]], [[South London Gallery]], the [[Institute of Contemporary Arts]], [[The Photographers' Gallery]] and [[Amgueddfa Cymru \u2013 National Museum Wales|Amgueddfa Cymru]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/here-are-the-museums-that-have-closed-due-to-coronavirus|title=Here are the museums that have closed (so far) due to coronavirus|last=McGivern|first=Hannah|last2=Kenney|first2=Nancy|date=14 March 2020|website=The Art Newspaper|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Many other organisations announced closures on the 17 and 18 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/arts/london-museums-galleries-exhibitions-closed-coronavirus-a4389351.html|title=The London galleries and museums that are closed due to coronavirus|last=Paskett|first=Zoe|date=17 March 2020|website=Evening Standard|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-51928526|title=Tate, V&A and Natural History Museum to close|date=2020-03-17|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-GB}}</ref> The [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] closed all ticketed properties by 20 March but aimed to keep gardens and parklands open, free of chargem so that people could access the open space whilst social distancing.\n\nThe planned major exhibition at the [[National Gallery]] in London of [[Artemisia Gentileschi]], set to open on April 4, was postponed for an indeterminate time due not only to the gallery's closure but also the inability of artworks on loan from Italy and America being unable to fly during the global shutdown in air traffic.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jones|first=Jonathan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2020/mar/16/artemisia-gentileschi-national-gallery-exhibition-postponed-coronavirus|title=With coronavirus, the curse of Artemisia Gentileschi strikes again|date=2020-03-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n'''North America'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |USA}}. [[The Broadway League]] announced on March 12 that all [[Broadway theatres]] would cease performances for at least a month, even though the New York State governor had at the time allowed them to continue at 50% capacity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/12/health/broadway-coronavirus-update/index.html|title=Broadway theaters to suspend all performances because of coronavirus|author1=Taylor Romine |author2=Eric Levenson |author3=Javi Morgado|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n'''Oceania'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Australia}}. Beginning from the second week of March Australian institutions began announcing reduced services, and then complete closures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wragge.github.io/closed-glams-covid19/|title=Australian GLAMs and COVID-19|website=closed-glams-covid19|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[Opera Australia]] announced it would close on the 15th.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://operawire.com/opera-australia-cancels-performances-due-to-coronavirus/|title=Opera Australia Cancels Performances Due to Coronavirus|date=2020-03-15|website=Opera Wire|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> On the 24th the national closure of all cultural institutions was required.\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |New Zealand}}. New Zealand implemented a policy on March 23 that all institutions would be closed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ndf.org.nz/covid19-and-nz-glams|title=COVID-19 and NZ GLAMs|website=National Digital Forum|language=en-NZ|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]] closed from 6pm March 20.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Campbell|first=Georgina|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12318548|title=Coronavirus: Te Papa museum to close for two weeks|date=20 March 2020|work=New Zealand Herald|access-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Auckland War Memorial Museum]] announced that it would close from March 21.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aucklandmuseum.com/service-pages/alerts/covid-19?utm_source=wordfly&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=TemporaryMuseumClosure&utm_content=version_A|title=Auckland Museum is temporarily closed}}</ref>\n\n'''South America'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Argentina}}. All the museums, cultural activities and gatherings were cancelled in the city of Buenos Aires on the 12th of March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clarin.com/cultura/coronavirus-argentina-disponen-cierre-temporario-museos-ciudad_0_Hgfv9C32.html|title=Coronavirus en Argentina: disponen el cierre temporario de todos los museos de la Ciudad|last=|website=www.clarin.com|language=es|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> National libraries continue to offer means of contact through the main educational website of the Ministry of Education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.educ.ar/recursos/151053/bibliotecas-en-casa-en-seguimos-conectados?from=150858&fbclid=IwAR3S3KjeZavdRV6gjOCfJxVUz6Xu5L0Eqfep7SBTT5l1RrOOKvuHQDML0tY|title=#BibliotecasEnCasa en Seguimos Educando - Educ.ar|website=www.educ.ar|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Brazil}}. Museums which have closed{{when|date=March 2020}} in Brazil include the Museum of Art of S\u00e3o Paulo Assis Chateaubriand, the Pinacoteca, the Ita\u00fa Cultural, the Museum of Contemporary Art of the University of S\u00e3o Paulo, the Institute Tomie Ohtake, the Institute Moreira Salles, and the Museum of Tomorrow in Rio de Janeiro and the Instituto Inhotim contemporary art centre in Brumadinho.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Adaptations==\nFacing at least several weeks of closure of their buildings and publicly-accessible spaces, many cultural sector organisations and individual artists turned to digital activities as a way to continue fulfilling their organisational mission and obtain or retain an audience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@kajsahartig/museums-delivering-value-online-some-thoughts-during-the-covid-19-crisis-193fc0a58d22|title=Museums delivering value online \u2014 some thoughts during the Covid-19 crisis|last=Hartig|first=Kajsa|date=2020-03-29|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Farago|first=Jason|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/arts/design/coronavirus-digital-artists.html|title=The Merry-Go-Round Stopped. What Sort of Art Will Emerge?|date=2020-03-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> For example, the [[BBC]] launched a \"virtual festival of the arts\" called ''Culture in quarantine.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2020/culture-in-quarantine|title=BBC - BBC Arts announces new programmes for Culture In Quarantine - Media Centre|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Having been the first country to enforce quarantine upon its population, museums in China were also the first to provide new digital services (primarily for a domestic audience, but to a lesser extent also internationally). In January the [[National Cultural Heritage Administration]] (NCHA) said they would \"encourage cultural heritage museums and institutions around the country to utilise existing digital resources and launch online exhibitions as appropriate, providing the public with safe and convenient online services.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/travel/news/chinas-museums-offer-online-exhibitions-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/ar-BBZEOr6|title=China's museums offer online exhibitions amid coronavirus outbreak|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ncha.gov.cn/art/2020/1/28/art_722_158541.html|title=\u5173\u4e8e\u5411\"\u535a\u7269\u9986\u7f51\u4e0a\u5c55\u89c8\u5e73\u53f0\"\u63d0\u4f9b\u7f51\u4e0a\u5c55\u89c8\u5185\u5bb9\u8d44\u6e90\u7684\u5021\u8bae\u4e66|website=www.ncha.gov.cn|publisher=[[National Cultural Heritage Administration]]|language=zh|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nMany institutions turned to their existing [[social media]] presences to engage their audience online. Quickly, the [[Twitter|Twitter hashtag]] #MuseumFromHome became particularly popular for museums sharing their content in innovative ways. Various institutions were singled out for particular praise by industry analysts for their successful social media content strategy during the shutdown. These included the [[Shedd Aquarium]] in Chicago for filming their penguins visiting other animals; the [[Royal Academy]] in London for asking its followers to draw their own artworks; and the [[National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum]] in Oklahoma for providing an authentic and unusual 'voice' to their social media - from their security guard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museumnext.com/article/museum-social-media-entertains-during-the-covid-19-crisis/|title=Museum Social Media Entertains During the COVID-19 Crisis|date=2020-03-19|website=MuseumNext|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boredpanda.com/national-cowboy-museum-head-of-security-twitter/|title=Cowboy Museum Puts Their Head Of Security In Charge Of Their Twitter, And His Tweets Are Hilariously Wholesome|website=Bored Panda|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Individual actors and musicians offered [[impromptu]] performances via their personal accounts from their homes \u2013 singing [[Cover version|covers]], performing live book or [[poetry readings]], or creatively live-streaming themselves doing both normal and unusual activities.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Stubbins|first=Sinead|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2020/mar/25/coronavirus-cabin-fever-the-best-celebrities-to-follow-from-robbie-williams-to-florence-pugh|title=Coronavirus cabin fever: the best celebrities to follow, from Robbie Williams to Florence Pugh|date=2020-03-25|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n\nVarious [[internet journalism]] and [[Industry association]]s published lists of new digitally-accessible arts and culture content for their country:\n{{Expand list|date=March 2020}}\n{{columns-list|colwidth=15em|style=width: 600px;|\n*{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Argentina}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buenosaires.gob.ar/culturaencasa|title=Cultura en casa|website=Buenos Aires Ciudad - Gobierno de la Ciudad Aut\u00f3noma de Buenos Aires|language=es|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n*{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Australia}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ozglam.info/s/updates/page/welcome|title=Australian GLAM updates|website=ozglam.info|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n*{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Ireland}} <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://irishmuseums.org/text-pages/irishmuseumsonline-content-and-resources|title=#IrishMuseumsOnline: content and resources|website=Irish Museums Association|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n*{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Italy}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalist.it/arti/2020/03/13/musei-chiusi-per-coronavirus-cosa-offrono-sul-web-e-social-mentre-iorestoacasa-2054444.html|title=Musei chiusi per Coronavirus: cosa offrono sul web e social mentre #iorestoacasa|website=Globalist|language=it|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ilfattoquotidiano.it/2020/03/18/coronavirus-dal-louvre-agli-uffizi-i-musei-chiusi-ora-si-visitano-online-cineteche-teatri-e-biblioteche-cosi-la-cultura-arriva-direttamente-a-casa/5739782/|title=Coronavirus, dal Louvre agli Uffizi, i musei chiusi ora si visitano online. Cinema, teatri e biblioteche: cos\u00ec la cultura arriva direttamente a casa|date=2020-03-18|website=Il Fatto Quotidiano|language=it-IT|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n*{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |UK}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museumsassociation.org/museums-journal/news/19032020-how-digital-platforms-be-used-to-support-musems-during-covid-19-crisis|title=How can digital platforms help museums connect to audiences during Covid-19 emergency|publisher=[[Museums Association]]|website=www.museumsassociation.org|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kidsinmuseums.org.uk/2020/03/10-museum-activities-to-keep-children-entertained/|title=10 museum activities to keep children entertained|date=2020-03-23|website=Kids in Museums|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===By sector===\n====[[Public aquarium|Aquaria]] and [[zoo]]s====\nSeveral institutions launched new [[webcams]] and [[livestreams]] of their animal habitats - sometimes while animals such as penguins would be taken by [[zookeeper|keepers]] to \"visit\" other animal enclosures.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Padilla|first=Mariel|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/us/coronavirus-zoos-webcams.html|title=Stuck at Home, You Can Still Explore the Zoo or Aquarium. Some Penguins Could, Too.|date=2020-03-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-25|last2=Vigdor|first2=Neil|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/travel/story/2020-03-20/virtual-touring|title=Watching animals helps. A lot. Here are the best webcams|date=2020-03-20|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n====[[Cinema]]====\n\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema}}\n\nThe production and release schedule of many films was suspended or delayed, with some awards ceremonies and festivals being cancelled entirely. March 2020 estimates were of approximately $5b losses for the industry.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shoard|first=Catherine|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/mar/06/cinema-coronavirus-projected-5bn-loss|title=Cinema bullish in the face of coronavirus despite projected $5bn loss|date=2020-03-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Examples of adaptations included the early [[Home video|home media]] release ([[Frozen II|''Frozen II'']]), [[Theatrical release|theatrical releases]] being cancelled entirely (''[[Lost in Russia]]''), and online premieres ([[Enter the Fat Dragon (2020 film)|''Enter the Fat Dragon'']]). \n\n====[[Libraries]]====\n[[File:National_Emergency_Library.png|thumb|right|the \"National Emergency Library\" of the Internet Archive]]\nOn 24 March, the [[Internet Archive]] announced the creation of a \"National Emergency Library\", which has suspended waitlists on 1.4m ebooks from their lending library \u2013 books that are not in the public domain according to US law \u2013 in order to ensure uninterrupted access to these books for educators and students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.archive.org/2020/03/24/announcing-a-national-emergency-library-to-provide-digitized-books-to-students-and-the-public/|title=Announcing a National Emergency Library to Provide Digitized Books to Students and the Public|last=|first=|date=24 March 2020|website=Internet Archive Blogs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2020/03/internet-archive-offers-thousands-of-copyrighted-books-for-free-online/|title=Internet Archive offers 1.4 million copyrighted books for free online|last=Lee|first=Timothy B.|date=2020-03-28|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Similarly, the [[National library of Israel]] announced it would be offering free audiobooks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/israel-news/national-library-offers-free-audiobooks-amid-coronavirus-closures-621664|title=National Library offers free audiobooks amid coronavirus closures|website=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> The Library of the [[National Congress of Argentina]] created activities including public readings and delivery of selected artworks through [[Instagram]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/cultura/2020/03/18/biblioteca-del-congreso-todas-las-actividades-online-durante-la-pandemia-del-coronavirus/|title=Biblioteca del Congreso: todas las actividades online durante la pandemia del coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=Infobae|language=es-ES|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n====[[Museums]]====\n{{Quote box\n|width     = 22em\n|border    = 1px\n|align     = right\n|fontsize  = 100%\n|salign    = center\n|quote     =\n\u201cThis year, the paint has more time to dry.\u201d<br> \nA statement from the [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]] announcing a delay to the [[Archibald Prize]] portraiture exhibition until after the health crisis, \"when art will be needed more than ever\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/art-and-design/paint-has-more-time-to-dry-archibald-prize-delayed-20200321-p54ck2.html|title='Paint has more time to dry': Archibald Prize delayed|date=21 March 2020|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n}}\n\nMany websites were rapidly updated to focus on digital resources. In mid-March the [[Museum Computer Network]] published an extensive \"Guide to Virtual Museum Resources, E-Learning, and Online Collections\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mcn.edu/a-guide-to-virtual-museum-resources/|title=The Ultimate Guide to Virtual Museum Resources|date=2020-03-15|website=MCN|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Lists also were published of fine-art museums with existing interactive services (notably those already \"partners\" of [[Google Arts & Culture]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/547919/2500-virtual-museum-tours-google-arts-culture/|title=2,500 Museums You Can Now Visit Virtually|date=2020-03-16|website=Hyperallergic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Philbrook Museum of Art]]'s rapid relaunch their website in late-March \u2013 in order \"for us all to spend some time practicing social distancing and experiencing the #MuseumFromHome\" \u2013 was described as a model example of how an institution could \"Reorganise, Reuse and Rethink\" its activities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museumnext.com/article/reorganise-reuse-get-creative-and-relaunch-lessons-from-philbrook/|title=Reorganise, Reuse, Rethink and Relaunch - Lessons from Philbrook|date=2020-03-21|website=MuseumNext|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Other specific examples included [[Europeana]] publishing a digital gallery of images relating to the theme of [[handwashing]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.europeana.eu/en/galleries/washing-your-hands|title=Washing your hands|website=www.europeana.eu|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> and the [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|Museum of New Zealand]] publishing a \"little page of calm\" (a reference to the 1997 bestselling book ''[[Little book of calm]]'').<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tepapa.govt.nz/discover-collections/read-watch-play/little-page-calm|title=The little page of calm|date=2020-03-16|website=Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa, Wellington, NZ|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n====[[Music]]====\nIndividually and collectively, [[musicians]] organised online performances, often via their own social media platforms. Some were especially planned and prepared; some were impromptu. For example, cellist [[Yo-Yo Ma|YoYo Ma]] used his social media account \"#songsofcomfort\" as a way to share music. His first offering was \"Going Home\" by [[Anton\u00edn Dvo\u0159\u00e1k|Antonin Dvo\u0159\u00e1k.]] Inspired by his example, others followed suit with their own at-home performances. The West Australian Symphony Orchestra renamed themselves the \"West Australian Social Distancing Orchestra\" and played a re-arranged version of ''[[Bol\u00e9ro]]'' by [[Maurice Ravel|Maurice Ravel. T]]<nowiki/>he quickly organised \"Instagram Live Music Festival\"''Isol Aid'' (a reference to [[Live Aid]]) of 72 Australian bands was broadcast on the weekend of 21\u201322 March. Each artist performed from wherever the were [[Isolation (health care)|self isolating]] and \"... play a 20-minute set streamed live on their Instagram accounts, and then tag-team the next artist to play\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/isol-aid-instagram-live-music-festival-coronavirus-covid-19/12072202|title=Isol-Aid is a stacked Aussie livestreaming music festival that's happening this weekend|last=Newstead|first=Al|date=2020-03-19|website=triple j|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://linktr.ee/isolaidfestival|title=@isolaidfestival|website=Linktree|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> while one amateur choir gathered the contributions of more than 1000 people from 18 countries to create a video performance of \u201cClose To You\u201d by [[The Carpenters]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HezxInuN1YA|title=Couch Choir - (They Long To Be) Close To You|last=|first=|date=22 March 2020|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In the middle of March, [[Bob Dylan]] released a single 17 minute new song called \"[[Murder Most Foul (song)|Murder Most Foul]]\", his first piece of original material in eight years.<ref>{{Cite news|last=McFadyen|first=Matthew|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/murder-most-foul-bob-dylan-s-surprise-song-for-the-viral-age-20200330-p54f8z.html|title=Murder Most Foul: Bob Dylan's surprise song for the viral age|date=30 March 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\nOther musicians, singers and songwriters adapted to the crisis by turning to teaching online.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lamond|first=Scott|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-26/coronavirus-cant-stop-the-music-as-online-lessons-in-demand/12089060|title=Coronavirus sees ARIA-winning musicians turn online teachers as students flock to lessons|date=26 March 2020|work=ABC News|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSeveral musical artists delayed the releases of albums due to the pandemic.<ref name=\"rstone1\">{{cite web |last1=Leight |first1=Elias |title=They Were Going to Be Spring's Biggest Albums -- Until COVID-19 Hit |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/album-delays-caused-by-covid-19-973870/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=30 March 2020}}</ref> [[Record Store Day]] was rescheduled from April 18 to June 20.<ref>{{cite web |title=Record Store Day 2020 Postponed Due to Coronavirus Concerns |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/record-store-day-2020-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-concerns/ |website=Pitchfork |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe following is a list of albums whose release dates have been rescheduled as the result of the coronavirus pandemic:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Artist\n!Album Title\n!Original date\n!Rescheduled date\n!Source\n|-\n|{{hs|1975, The}}[[The 1975]]\n|''[[Notes on a Conditional Form]]''\n|April 24\n|May 22\n|<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shaffer |first1=Claire |title=The 1975 Postpone 'Notes on a Conditional Form' Release Date (Again) |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-1975-notes-on-a-conditional-form-delayed-975183/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Biffy Clyro]]\n|''[[A Celebration of Endings]]''\n|May 15\n|August 14\n|<ref name=\"spin1\"/>\n|-\n|[[DMA's]]\n|''The Glow''\n|April 24\n|July 10\n|<ref name=\"spin1\"/>\n|-\n|[[Jarvis Cocker|Jarv Is]]\n|''[[Beyond the Pale (Jarv Is album)|Beyond the Pale]]''\n|May 1\n|September 4\n|<ref name=\"spin1\"/>\n|-\n|{{hs|Gallagher, Liam}}[[Liam Gallagher]]\n|''MTV Unplugged''\n|April 24\n|TBA\n|<ref name=\"spin1\"/>\n|-\n|[[Haim (band)|Haim]]\n|''[[Women in Music Pt. III|Women in Music Pt. III]]''\n|April 24\n|Summer 2020\n|<ref name=\"spin1\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Here Are the Album Release Dates That Have Changed |url=https://www.spin.com/2020/03/coronavirus-here-are-the-album-release-dates-that-have-changed/ |website=Spin |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Hinds (band)|Hinds]]\n|''[[The Prettiest Curse]]''\n|April 3\n|June 5\n|<ref name=\"spin1\"/>\n|-\n|{{hs|Keys, Alicia}}[[Alicia Keys]]\n|''[[Alicia (album)|Alicia]]''\n|March 20\n|May 15\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=A list of albums delayed due to coronavirus (Updated) |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/a-list-of-albums-delayed-due-to-coronavirus__29162/ |website=www.officialcharts.com |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Lady Gaga]]\n|''[[Chromatica]]''\n|March 25\n|TBA\n|<ref name=\"spin1\"/>\n|-\n|{{hs|Lemon Twigs, The}}[[The Lemon Twigs]]\n|''Songs for the General Public''\n|May 1\n|August 21\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=The Lemon Twigs\u2019 new album has been delayed because of the coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.thelineofbestfit.com/news/latest-news/the-lemon-twigs-new-album-delayed-because-of-coronavirus-pandemic |website=The Line of Best Fit |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{hs|McKenna, Declan}}[[Declan McKenna]]\n|''Zeros''\n|May 15\n|August 21\n|<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clarke |first1=Patrick |title=Declan McKenna delays the release of new album \u2018Zeros\u2019 and cancels tour due to coronavirus crisis |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/declan-mckenna-delays-the-release-of-new-album-zeros-and-cancels-tour-due-to-coronavirus-crisis-2634304 |website=NME |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{hs|Nelson, Willie}}[[Willie Nelson]]\n|''[[First Rose of Spring]]''\n|April 24\n|July 3\n|<ref name=\"spin1\"/>\n|-\n|{{hs|Pretenders, The}}[[The Pretenders]]\n|''Hate for Sale''\n|May 1\n|July 17\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=The Pretenders Announce New Album Hate for Sale, Share \"The Buzz\": Stream |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/03/the-pretenders-hate-for-sale-the-buzz-stream/ |website=Consequence of Sound |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{hs|Price, Margo}}[[Margo Price]]\n|''[[That's How Rumors Get Started]]''\n|May 8\n|Summer 2020\n|<ref name=\"spin1\"/>\n|-\n|{{hs|Smith, Sam}}[[Sam Smith]]\n|[[Upcoming Sam Smith album|Currently untitled]]\n|May 1\n|TBA\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=Sam Smith Pushing Back and Changing Title of New Album |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/sam-smith-pushing-back-and-changing-title-of-new-album/ |website=Pitchfork |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\nIn contrast to the postponements, some musical acts, such as [[Dua Lipa]] and [[Sufjan Stevens]], moved up the release dates of their upcoming albums.<ref name=\"sgum1\">{{cite web |last1=Rettig |first1=James |title=HAIM, Dua Lipa, Willie Nelson, & Sufjan Stevens Among Artists Moving Album Release Dates Amid Pandemic |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2077667/dua-lipa-willie-nelson-sufjan-stevens-among-artists-moving-album-release-dates-amid-pandemic/news/ |website=Stereogum |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Others, such as [[Nine Inch Nails]] and [[Phish]], released new albums with little or no notice.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Farokhmanesh |first1=Megan |title=Nine Inch Nails just released two new albums for free |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/26/21195266/nine-inch-nails-new-albums-just-ghosts-v-vi-free-download |website=The Verge |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kreps |first1=Daniel |title=Phish to Debut New Album 'Sigma Oasis' During April 1st Livestream |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/phish-new-album-sigma-oasis-976437/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====[[Performing arts]]====\nNew (or a newly expanded range) free [[online streaming]] of previously recorded theatrical performances was provided by many institutions.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Convery|first=Stephanie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2020/mar/20/livestreaming-schedule-music-art-literature-and-events-from-australia-and-beyond|title=Livestreaming schedule: music, art, literature and events from Australia and beyond|date=2020-03-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-26|last2=Rawson|first2=Sharnee|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> For example, the [[Metropolitan Opera]] of New York broadcast a new opera each evening, including an entire [[Ring Cycle]] performed during the 2010\u201312 seasons, via their own app,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/in-wake-of-season-cancellation-metropolitan-opera-continues-free-streaming-series-with-a-week-of-wagner|title=In Wake of Season Cancellation, Metropolitan Opera Continues Free Streaming Series With a Week of Wagner|last=McPhee|first=Ryan|date=2020-03-23|website=[[Playbill]]|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> and the [[Bolshoi Ballet]] company of Moscow made available six of their recorded performances via [[YouTube]] for 24 hours each.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2020/03/27/spend-an-evening-at-the-bolshoi-a69775|title=Spend an Evening at the Bolshoi|last=|first=|date=2020-03-27|website=The Moscow Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-russia-bolshoi-idUSKBN21E35D|title=Russia's Bolshoi Theater goes online as coronavirus curbs public life|date=2020-03-27|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-29|language=en}}</ref> The [[West End theatre|West End]] production of ''[[The Wind in the Willows (musical)|The Wind in the Willows]]'' was also streamed for UK residents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://londonist.com/london/theatre-and-arts/wind-in-the-willows-streaming-west-end|title=You Can Screen The West End's Wind In The Willows Online For Free|date=2020-03-18|website=Londonist|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nIndividual actors of the first rank, such as [[Patrick Stewart]] and [[Sam Neill]] used their skill from isolation to entertain, support and get out the message that \"we really need to be in this together and that this has to take the form of being apart\" as Neill described his singing and reciting. His contribution was described as a skilled actor \"pretending to be an ordinary joe amusing himself beyond his capacity\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Craven|first=Peter|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/movies/when-the-going-got-tough-sam-neill-got-out-his-ukulele-20200330-p54fd8.html|title=When the going got tough, Sam Neill got out his ukulele|date=1 April 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Stewart, a trained Shakespearian actor with a \"deep velvety\" voice, broadcast himself reading one [[Shakespearean sonnet]] each day via [[Instagram]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://londonist.com/london/books-and-poetry/patrick-stewart-is-treating-twitter-to-one-shakespearan-sonnet-a-day-during-lockdown|title=Patrick Stewart Is Treating Twitter To One Shakespeare Sonnet A Day During Lockdown|date=2020-03-25|website=Londonist|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>  \n\n==Impacts==\n===Budgets and employment===\n{{see also|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nDue to the closures, revenues for cultural organisations reliant on ticket sales were expected to cause devastating effects upon revenues, with consequent impacts upon organisational staffing, and on independent artists and professionals. This is due to the fact that the arts and culture is a sector of national economies characterised by particularly a high proportion of self-employment.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/arts-council-england-emergency-relief-fund-1814829|title=Arts Council England Has Launched a $190 Million Emergency Relief Package for Creative Organizations and Artists|date=2020-03-25|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> For example, by the 20th of March the [[Cirque du Soleil]] had [[laid off]] 95% of its workforce and closed [[traveling circus]] performances operating in seven countries,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/cirque-de-soleil-canada-coronavirus-staff-fired-1493386|title=Cirque du Soleil lays off 95 percent of its workforce after coronavirus forces closure of all its shows globally|last=Cole|first=Brendan|date=2020-03-20|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> The world commercial art market declined 5% in 2019 compared to the previous year, and is expected to decline further in 2020 \u2013 with 6 of the world's 10 largest auction houses operating exclusively in China. Major art fairs such as [[Hong Kong Arts Festival]] and [[Art Basel]] were cancelled, furthering a shift towards online purchases and the creation of VIP \"online viewing rooms\" rather than physical displaying at [[art auctions]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/the-coronavirus-pandemic-corona-panic-is-shaking-up-worlds-global-art-market-starting-in-hong-kong/a-52651815|title=The coronavirus is shaking up the world's art market in unexpected ways|publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]]|website=DW.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nArts and culture sector budgetary and employment reports from individual countries included:<br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Australia}}. [[Opera Australia]] \u2013 the nation's largest [[performing arts]] company \u2013 temporarily stood down nearly all its staff<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/exit-stage-left-opera-australia-leads-arts-shutdown-20200325-p54dq1|title=Exit stage left: Opera Australia leads arts shutdown|date=2020-03-26|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> amid speculation it would also need to sell major assets in order to avoid [[bankruptcy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/opera-australia-looks-to-sell-offs-to-stay-afloat-20200316-p54ai2.html|title=Opera Australia looks to sell-offs to stay afloat|last=Galvin|first=Nick|date=2020-03-16|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> By the 23rd of March, 255,000 cultural events had been cancelled with an estimated revenue loss of $A280 million, self reported through the crowdsourced website ILostMyGig.net.au.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/coronavirus-what-the-latest-stimulus-measures-mean-for-australian-artists-and-arts-organisations-134233|title=Coronavirus: what the latest stimulus measures mean for Australian artists and arts organisations|last=Caust|first=Jo|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Italy}}. In March, when many institutions closed for the first time since [[WWII]], the state-funded museum sector had been valued at \u20ac27 billion or 1.6% of national GDP \u2013 slightly smaller than the agriculture sector.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/coronavirus-l-impatto-negativo-chiusure-musei-che-valgono-l-16percento-pil-AC4pFCMB|title=Coronavirus, l'impatto negativo delle chiusure sui musei (che valgono l'1,6% del Pil)|website=Il Sole 24 ORE|language=it|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |USA}}. As the pandemic spread and closures became the standard not the exception, institutions started publishing expected revenue shortfall calculations, began to fire staff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AMTransparency/status/1242869675425443840|title=This will be a thread for tracking museum layoff news.|date=2020-03-25|website=Twitter|publisher=Art + Museum Transparency|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> For example: the [[Metropolitan opera]] expects to lose $60m in revenue;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Woolfe|first=Zachary|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/19/arts/music/metropolitan-opera-coronavirus.html|title=Metropolitan Opera Cancels Season Over Virus and Faces $60 Million Loss|date=2020-03-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> the [[Metropolitan Museum]] expects to lose $100m in revenue with likely layoffs;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Pogrebin|first=Robin|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/arts/design/met-museum-coronavirus-closure.html|title=Met Museum Prepares for $100 Million Loss and Closure Till July|date=2020-03-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and SFMOMA [[furlough]]ed 300 staff in the expectation of a 40% decrease in revenue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/arts/13877653/sfmoma-to-lay-off-or-furlough-over-300-museum-staff|title=SFMOMA to Lay Off or Furlough Over 300 Museum Staff|last=Hotchkiss|first=Sarah|date=2020-03-27|website=[[KQED]]|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The [[Science Museum of Minnesota]] expected to lose $15m in revenue over three months. Consequently, it \"temporarily\" [[laid off]] most of its staff in an announcement via a [[Google Hangouts]] videocall in late March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.startribune.com/minnesota-science-museum-children-s-museum-lay-off-most-staff-in-wake-of-covid-19-outbreak/569063662/|title=Science Museum of Minnesota, Children's Museum temporarily lay off most staff in wake of COVID-19|website=Star Tribune|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Meanwhile, staff across the museum began to unionise, even though \"[[Social distancing]] orders prevent the in-person meetings required to sign the cards required to file for union elections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tinyletter.com/artandmuseumtransparency/letters/art-museum-transparency-newsletter-2-march-2020|title=Art + Museum Transparency Newsletter #2 -- March 2020|last=|first=|date=2020-03-26|website=artandmuseumtransparency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Financial stimulus ===\nWith the extensive financial disruption across all areas of the economy, many governments announced [[Stimulus (economics)|fiscal stimulus]] and [[Bailout|economic bailout]] packages which included specific resources for the arts and cultural sectors. Equally, various [[charities]] and industry bodies raised funds to support their sector.\n\nArts and culture sector financial stimulus packages from individual countries included:\n{{Expand list|date=March 2020}}\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Australia}}. petition of over 50 arts and culture organisations (including peak bodies from the music, dance, visual arts, museums, writers' and indigenous arts groups) requested a financial aid package \"...to a value of 2% of the $111.7 billion [cultural and creative] industry\" and requesting the Prime Minister \"...issue a public statement recognising the value of our industry to all Australians\" and noting that the industry had not yet recovered from the impact of the [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://visualarts.net.au/news-opinion/2020/creative-industry-unites/|title=Creative industry unites to secure Australia's cultural life|website=NAVA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Germany}}. The minister for culture [[Monika Gr\u00fctters]] declared that \"artists are not only indispensable, but also vital, especially now.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/german-bailout-50-billion-1815396|title=Germany Has Rolled Out a Staggering \u20ac50 Billion Aid Package For Small Businesses That Boosts Artists and Galleries\u2014and Puts Other Countries to Shame|date=2020-03-25|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The statement was made while announcing a \u20ac50 billion stimulus package for small business and freelancers \u2013 explicitly including the creative sectors.\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Sweden}}. The Swedish Minister of Culture [[Amanda Lind]] presented a 1 billion [[Swedish krona|SEK]] support package for sports and culture, where 500 million SEK was earmarked for culture (not including government agencies like the [[Royal Dramatic Theatre]] and [[Kungliga Operan]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=En miljard i akut st\u00f6d till kultur och idrott|url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/coronaviruset/en-miljard-i-akut-stod-till-kultur-och-idrott/|publisher=Expressen|access-date=2020-03-25|language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |UK}}. [[The Film and TV Charity]] created an emergency relief fund in order to \"provide emergency short-term relief to active workers and freelancers who have been directly affected by the closure of productions across the UK\", with an initial donation of \u00a31m from [[Netflix]] and by \u00a3500,000 from the [[BBC]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/bfi-uk-film-and-tv-charity-set-up-covid-19-emergency-relief-fund-with-1m-donation-from-netflix-1202890966/|title=BFI & UK Film And TV Charity Set Up Covid-19 Emergency Relief Fund With \u00a31M Donation From Netflix|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=2020-03-24|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/bbc-donates-to-covid-19-emergency-relief-fund-1202894127/|title=BBC Joins Netflix In Making $600,000 Donation To Coronavirus Emergency Relief Fund|last=Kanter|first=Jake|date=2020-03-27|website=Deadline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The [[Museums Association]] called upon the UK government to divert \u00a3120m that was intended for the [[Festival of Britain 2022]] to bail out museums in financial distress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museumsassociation.org/museums-journal/news/17032020-museum-closures-coronavirus-covid-19|title=Museums and galleries close as coronavirus emergency intensifies|last=Kendall Adams|first=Geraldine|date=17 March 2020|website=Museums Association|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" /> [[Arts Council England]] announced \u00a3160 million would be made available for arts organisations, including \u00a350 million for organisations it does not usually fund and \u00a320 million for individual and freelance artists.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |USA}}. A petition was begun by the [[American Alliance of Museums]] to request that the museum sector was included in any future [[economic stimulus]] from the United States government,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congressweb.com/AAM/67|title=Tell Congress: Include Museums in COVID-19 Economic Relief|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> while the Metropolitan museum was more specific \u2013 requesting $4 billion for at-risk museums.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/metropolitan-museum-of-art-congress-1813665|title=The Metropolitan Museum of Art Is Calling on the US Government to Bail Out At-Risk Museums With $4 Billion in Aid|date=2020-03-24|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nIn late March the United States federal government announced a $2 trillion economic stimulus package. It included: \"$75 million for the [[National Endowment for the Arts]] and $75 million for the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]], which can pass on the money to institutions that need it. Another $50 million was designated to the [[Institute of Museum and Library Services]], which distributes funds to museums and libraries.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Jacobs|first=Julia|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/24/arts/coronavirus-arts-bailout.html|title=Arts Groups, Facing Their Own Virus Crisis, Get a Piece of the Stimulus|date=2020-03-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> While a common argument in the USA against the cultural sector receiving stimulus funding was that \"Arts groups may be 'nice,' but they\u2019re far from 'necessary.'\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Copyright ===\nAcademic librarians in the United States made public statements on the applicability and importance of the role of the [[fair use]] copyright exception for \"Emergency Remote Teaching & Research\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/document/d/10baTITJbFRh7D6dHVVvfgiGP2zqaMvm0EHHZYf2cBRk/mobilebasic?urp=gmail_link|title=Public Statement: Fair Use & Emergency Remote Teaching & Research|website=docs.google.com|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[Cornell University Library]] made the advice explicit, noting in a new official library policy recommending, \"...that faculty may scan course material in amounts that may exceed customary fair use limits under normal circumstances. Fair use provides flexibility to permit faculty scan broader amounts of course material than normal during these exigent circumstances.\" and noted that library staff were no longer allowed to work on-site and therefore not able to scan materials on behalf of teaching staff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://copyright.cornell.edu/covid|title=COVID-19 & Copyright at Cornell {{!}} Copyright Information Center|website=copyright.cornell.edu|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nThe libraries of universities and of the [[National Research Council (Italy)|National Research Council]] in Italy petitioned [[academic publishers]] to provide temporary [[open access]] to publications in order to medical staff, scientific researchers, and the general public access during the national emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.centumcellae.it/cronaca/appello-per-il-diritto-di-accesso-alla-conoscenza-scientifica-in-stato-di-emergenza/|title=APPELLO PER IL DIRITTO DI ACCESSO ALLA CONOSCENZA SCIENTIFICA IN STATO DI EMERGENZA|last=|first=|date=2020-03-19|website=Centumcellae|language=it-IT|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n[[LeVar Burton]], host of [[Reading Rainbow]], announced his desire to perform live-streamed readings of books for his podcast ''LeVar Reads'' but that copyright law was unclear as to whether this was allowed. [[Neil Gaiman]] replied by twitter giving permission to read any of his works.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/939vjv/please-dont-sue-levar-burton-for-reading-soothing-stories-to-scared-children|title=Please Don't Sue LeVar Burton for Reading Soothing Stories to Scared Children|last=Cole|first=Samantha|date=2020-03-26|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nVarious online training workshops were organised for cultural heritage to learn about relevant risks and [[Copyright exceptions|exceptions to copyright]] when providing online services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/open-glam/copyright-open-access-for-glams-in-the-age-of-covid-19-1213b67a0e21|title=Copyright & Open Access for GLAMs in the age of COVID-19|date=2020-03-24|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Equally, [[digital strategy]] workshops<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usingdata.com/usingdata/2020/3/19/free-strategy-workshops-march-23-april-3|title=Free strategy workshops March 23 \u2013 April 3|website=Usingdata|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> and live Q&A sessions with experts were organised.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AAMers/status/1242798776655413249|title=What #COVID19 questions do you want to pose to the museum field? Comment below or DM us to include it in our #MuseumsDiscussCOVID19 Tweet chat! TODAY 3-4 pm|publisher=American Alliance of Museums|date=2020-03-25|website=Twitter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n=== New cultural works ===\n\nWith thorough and global disruption society to an unprecedented level, there is the expectation of many and diverse cultural works created which reference or are inspired by the pandemic and its effects. One gallery director said: \"There will definitely be an explosion in new material.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dye|first=Josh|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/art-and-design/perplexing-and-confusing-art-gallery-of-nsw-director-grapples-with-coronavirus-crisis-20200327-p54emd.html|title='Perplexing and confusing': Art Gallery of NSW director grapples with coronavirus crisis|date=28 March 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>{{Expand list|date=March 2020}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema]]\n* [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the arts and cultural heritage}}\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|arts]]\n[[Category:2020 in arts]]\n[[Category:Cultural heritage]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impact_of_the_2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic_on_the_arts_and_cultural_heritage"}
{"title_page": "Benno Bikes", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Benno Bikes|timestamp=20200401010541|year=2020|month=April|day=1|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Benno Bikes|date=1 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Benno Bikes\n| logo             = Benno Boost E with accessories.jpg\n| logo_caption     = Benno Bikes bicycle Boost E with accessories\n| logo_size        = \n| type             = Private\n| industry         = [[Electric bicycle]]s, [[Bicycles]]\n| foundation       = 2015\n| founder          = Benno B\u00e4nziger\n| location         = \n| location_city    = [[Del Mar, California]]\n| locations        = \n| area_served      = \n| key_people       = Benno B\u00e4nziger (CEO)\n| products         = [[Electric bicycle]]s, accessories and related components\n| services         = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| footnotes        = \n| location_country = United States\n| homepage         = {{url|https://bennobikes.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Benno Bikes''' is a bicycle brand and manufacturer of [[electric bicycle]]s, [[Freight bicycle|cargo]] and [[Hybrid bicycle|comfort bikes]], as well as cargo accessories and bicycle parts. Founded<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bike-eu.com/home/nieuws/2016/04/former-electra-co-founder-launches-benno-bikes-10126161|title=Former Electra Co-Founder Launches Benno Bikes|last=Beckendorff|first=Jo|date=2016-04-29|website=Bike Europe|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> in 2015 by Benno B\u00e4nziger in [[Del Mar, California]],<ref name=\"Neither\"/><ref name=\n\"Strickland\">{{cite news |work=[[Bicycling (magazine)|Bicycling]] |title=The Benno Boost E Brings Beauty to E-Cargo Bikes |quote=This highly-functional E-cargo bike is also wonderfully designed. |first1=Bill |last1=Strickland |date=March 9, 2017 |url=https://www.bicycling.com/bikes-gear/a20027408/the-benno-boost-e-brings-beauty-to-e-cargo-bikes/ |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> Benno Bikes products are currently sold by more than 200 independently owned cycling stores in the United States and Canada. Outside North America, Benno Bikes has distribution partners<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bennobikes.com/where-to-buy/|title=Dealer Locations and International Distributors|date=2020-03-30|website=Benno Bikes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> in more than 15 countries worldwide with Germany, France, the United Kingdom,<ref name=\"Everett\">{{cite news |title=Ison to showcase Benno Bikes at Corebike |url=https://cyclingindustry.news/ison-to-showcase-benno-bikes-at-corebike/ |work=[[Cycling Industry News]]|date=20 January 2020 |first1=Hayley |last1=Everett |quote=Benno Bikes prides itself on its \u2018e-Tility\u2019 offering; creating everyday e-Bikes engineered with a blend of ride dynamics, cargo capacity and aesthetics. |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Company uses Bosch motors, and is seen as being in the forefront in the e-bike industry.<ref name=\"Everett\"/><ref name=\"Montgomery\">{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/mikemontgomery/2018/11/26/7-mile-shoes-and-electric-bikes-a-story-of-innovation/#50160352931c |work=[[Forbes]] |date=November 26, 2018 |title=7-Mile Shoes And Electric Bikes: A Story Of Innovation |first1=Mike |last1=Montgomery |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt tries to create bikes that are an amalgum of being an every day cruiser, with some cargo carrying capacity.<ref name=\"Everett\"/>  This could make them a replacement for an automobile.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://electricbikereview.com/benno/boost-e-10d/ |title=Benno Boost E 10D Review |work=Electric Bike Review  |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Sherry\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bicycling.com/bikes-gear/a19595658/benno-ejoy-9d-ebike/ |title=The Benno eJoy 9D E-Bike Will Help You Conquer the World: MEET THE ALUMINUM STEP-THROUGH CRUISER BIKE THAT COULD REPLACE YOUR CAR |first1=Jennifer |last1=Sherry |date=March 28, 2018 |work=Bicycling |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe company sells several different models: Benno 2020 The RemiDemi; and is award-winning Boost E.<ref name=\"Everett\"/> Depending on owner preference, and using Bosch Performance Line CX Electric motor, the bikes combine power and stout design. The Boose E is \"the choice of professional rescue teams, adventurists, bike couriers and everyday suburban explorers.\"  The eJoy seeks to compete with vintage [[Vespa]]s.<ref name=\"Everett\"/>\n\nBen Luster from Benno Bikes will be flying into Corebike from t Switzerland,{{efn-ua|[[Air Zermatt]] has acquired a Benno bike and serves as a \"brand ambassador.\" \"The exclusively produced copy is primarily intended to serve the flight assistants as a means of transportation on flat terrain.\"<ref name=\"Neither\">{{cite news |work=[[Tageblatt|Tageblatt]] |language=German |title=Thanks to the start-up from Appenzell: The Benno Bike is now also conquering the Swiss market |first1=Claudio |last1=Neither |date=March 25, 2019 |url=https://www.tagblatt.ch/ostschweiz/appenzellerland/das-benno-bike-erobert-nun-auch-in-der-schweiz-den-markt-dank-eines-start-ups-aus-appenzell-ld.1105101|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>}} Norway, Australia and New Zealand among them.\n== Background ==\nBefore starting Benno Bikes, Benno B\u00e4nziger co-founded the [[Electra Bicycle Company]] with business partner Jeano Erforth in 1993.<ref name=\"Neither\"/> Electra was \"a leading lifestyle brand\"<ref name=\"Neither\"/> that was acquired by a private equity group in 2007 and later sold<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bicycleretailer.com/north-america/2014/01/06/trek-announces-acquisition-electra#.UssD6NJDv84|title=Trek announces acquisition of Electra|last=BRAIN|date=2014-01-06|website=Bicycle Retailer|publisher=|url-status=live}}</ref> to [[Trek Bicycle Company]], in 2014.\n\nBenno Bikes Swiss GmbH was founded in June 2017, by Swiss inventor Samuel Weishaupt.<ref name=\"Neither\"/>\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=upper-alpha}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Electric bicycles]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Benno Bikes|timestamp=20200401010541|year=2020|month=April|day=1|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Benno Bikes|date=1 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Benno Bikes\n| logo             = Benno Boost E with accessories.jpg\n| logo_caption     = Benno Bikes bicycle Boost E with accessories\n| logo_size        = \n| type             = Private\n| industry         = [[Electric bicycle]]s, [[Bicycles]]\n| foundation       = 2015\n| founder          = Benno B\u00e4nziger\n| location         = \n| location_city    = [[Del Mar, California]]\n| locations        = \n| area_served      = \n| key_people       = Benno B\u00e4nziger (CEO)\n| products         = [[Electric bicycle]]s, accessories and related components\n| services         = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| footnotes        = \n| location_country = United States\n| homepage         = {{url|https://bennobikes.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Benno Bikes''' is a bicycle brand and manufacturer of [[electric bicycle]]s, [[Freight bicycle|cargo]] and [[Hybrid bicycle|comfort bikes]], as well as cargo accessories and bicycle parts. Founded<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bike-eu.com/home/nieuws/2016/04/former-electra-co-founder-launches-benno-bikes-10126161|title=Former Electra Co-Founder Launches Benno Bikes|last=Beckendorff|first=Jo|date=2016-04-29|website=Bike Europe|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> in 2015 by Benno B\u00e4nziger in [[Del Mar, California]],<ref name=\"Neither\"/><ref name=\n\"Strickland\">{{cite news |work=[[Bicycling (magazine)|Bicycling]] |title=The Benno Boost E Brings Beauty to E-Cargo Bikes |quote=This highly-functional E-cargo bike is also wonderfully designed. |first1=Bill |last1=Strickland |date=March 9, 2017 |url=https://www.bicycling.com/bikes-gear/a20027408/the-benno-boost-e-brings-beauty-to-e-cargo-bikes/ |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> Benno Bikes products are currently sold by more than 200 independently owned cycling stores in the United States and Canada. Outside North America, Benno Bikes has distribution partners<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bennobikes.com/where-to-buy/|title=Dealer Locations and International Distributors|date=2020-03-30|website=Benno Bikes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> in more than 15 countries worldwide with Germany, France, the United Kingdom,<ref name=\"Everett\">{{cite news |title=Ison to showcase Benno Bikes at Corebike |url=https://cyclingindustry.news/ison-to-showcase-benno-bikes-at-corebike/ |date=20 January 2020 |first1=Hayley |last1=Everett |quote=Benno Bikes prides itself on its \u2018e-Tility\u2019 offering; creating everyday e-Bikes engineered with a blend of ride dynamics, cargo capacity and aesthetics. |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Company uses Bosch motors, and is seen as being in the forefront in the e-bike industry.<ref name=\"Everett\"/><ref name=\"Montgomery\">{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/mikemontgomery/2018/11/26/7-mile-shoes-and-electric-bikes-a-story-of-innovation/#50160352931c |work=[[Forbes]] |date=November 26, 2018 |title=7-Mile Shoes And Electric Bikes: A Story Of Innovation |first1=Mike |last1=Montgomery |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt tries to create bikes that are an amalgum of being an every day cruiser, with some cargo carrying capacity.<ref name=\"Everett\"/>  This could make them a replacement for an automobile.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://electricbikereview.com/benno/boost-e-10d/ |title=Benno Boost E 10D Review |work=Electric Bike Review  |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Sherry\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bicycling.com/bikes-gear/a19595658/benno-ejoy-9d-ebike/ |title=The Benno eJoy 9D E-Bike Will Help You Conquer the World: MEET THE ALUMINUM STEP-THROUGH CRUISER BIKE THAT COULD REPLACE YOUR CAR |first1=Jennifer |last1=Sherry |date=March 28, 2018 |work=Bicycling |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe company sells several different models: Benno 2020 The RemiDemi; and is award-winning Boost E.<ref name=\"Everett\"/> Depending on owner preference, and using Bosch Performance Line CX Electric motor, the bikes combine power and stout design. The Boose E is \"the choice of professional rescue teams, adventurists, bike couriers and everyday suburban explorers.\"  The eJoy seeks to compete with vintage [[Vespa]]s.<ref name=\"Everett\"/>\n\nBen Luster from Benno Bikes will be flying into Corebike from t Switzerland,{{efn-ua|[[Air Zermatt]] has acquired a Benno bike and serves as a \"brand ambassador.\" \"The exclusively produced copy is primarily intended to serve the flight assistants as a means of transportation on flat terrain.\"<ref name=\"Neither\">{{cite news |work=[[Tageblatt|Tageblatt]] |language=German |title=Thanks to the start-up from Appenzell: The Benno Bike is now also conquering the Swiss market |first1=Claudio |last1=Neither |date=March 25, 2019 |url=https://www.tagblatt.ch/ostschweiz/appenzellerland/das-benno-bike-erobert-nun-auch-in-der-schweiz-den-markt-dank-eines-start-ups-aus-appenzell-ld.1105101|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>}} Norway, Australia and New Zealand among them.\n== Background ==\nBefore starting Benno Bikes, Benno B\u00e4nziger co-founded the [[Electra Bicycle Company]] with business partner Jeano Erforth in 1993.<ref name=\"Neither\"/> Electra was \"a leading lifestyle brand\"<ref name=\"Neither\"/> that was acquired by a private equity group in 2007 and later sold<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bicycleretailer.com/north-america/2014/01/06/trek-announces-acquisition-electra#.UssD6NJDv84|title=Trek announces acquisition of Electra|last=BRAIN|date=2014-01-06|website=Bicycle Retailer|publisher=|url-status=live}}</ref> to [[Trek Bicycle Company]], in 2014.\n\nBenno Bikes Swiss GmbH was founded in June 2017, by Swiss inventor Samuel Weishaupt.<ref name=\"Neither\"/>\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=upper-alpha}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Electric bicycles]]\n", "name_user": "7&6=thirteen", "label": "safe", "comment": "ref form", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benno_Bikes"}
{"title_page": "Yamina (political alliance)", "text_new": "{{short description|Israeli electoral alliance}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Yamina\n| foundation = 29 July 2019 (first time)<br>15 January 2020 (revival)\n| dissolution = 10 October 2019 (first time)\n| country = Israel\n| ideology = [[Zionism]]<br>[[National conservatism]]<br>[[Economic liberalism]]<br>[[Judicial restraint]]<br>[[Israeli settlements|Settler]] interests<br>'''Factions:'''<br>[[Religious conservatism]]<br>[[Religious Zionism]]<br>[[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] interests<br>[[Right-wing populism]]\n| affiliation1 = [[New Right (Israel)|New Right]]<br>[[Tkuma (political party)|National Union]]<br>[[The Jewish Home]]\n| affiliation1_title = Member parties\n| leader = [[Naftali Bennett]]\n| native_name = {{Hebrew|\u05d9\u05de\u05d9\u05e0\u05d4}}\n| logo = File:Yamina logo.svg\n| logo_size = 135px\n| colorcode = {{Yamina/meta/color}}\n| colours = {{Color box|{{Yamina/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|#007DB0|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|#F5711F|border=darkgray}}\n{{Color box|#FFFFFF|border=darkgray}}\n| slogan = Israel wants to go right.\n| seats1_title = [[Knesset]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|6|120|hex={{Yamina/meta/color}}}}\n| symbol = {{hebrew|\u05d8\u05d1}}\n| position = [[Right-wing]] to [[Far-right politics|far-right]]\n| website = {{URL|https://yemina.co.il}}\n| headquarters =\n}}\n\n'''Yamina''' ({{Lang-he-n|\u05d9\u05de\u05d9\u05e0\u05d4}}, lit. ''Rightwards'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/267286|title=United Right to run under name 'Yemina'|work=[[Arutz Sheva]]|date=12 August 2019|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref> is an Israeli [[political alliance]] of [[right-wing]] to [[far-right]] parties, that was originally configured as the [[New Right (Israel)|New Right]] and the [[Union of Right-Wing Parties]] (a union of [[The Jewish Home]] and [[Tkuma (political party)|Tkuma]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/New-Right-and-URP-seal-political-union-deal-597080|title=Right-wing parties form alliance to be led by Shaked |work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |date=30 July 2019 |author=Jeremy Sharon}}</ref> The current incarnation of the alliance includes the [[New Right (Israel)|New Right]], The Jewish Home and Tkuma.<ref name=as15jan>{{cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/274617|title=Bennett, Peretz, Smotrich agree to joint run without Ben Gvir|work=[[Arutz Sheva]]|author=[[Staff writer]]|date=15 January 2020|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe list was created ahead of the [[September 2019 Israeli legislative election]], in which Yamina secured seven seats in the Knesset.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel-Elections/Israel-elections-results-based-on-counted-ballots-12-am-602045 |title=95% of votes counted: 33 seats for Blue & White, 32 for Likud |work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |date=18 September 2019}}</ref> The alliance was expected to split on 6 October, with the New Right as its own faction while Tkuma and the Jewish Home will stay together, though the alliance continued to negotiate as a single bloc in the aftermath of the election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Yamina-to-officially-split-on-Sunday-603705|title=Yamina to officially split on Sunday |work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=4 October 2019}}</ref> The meeting on 6 October was postponed, with some citing disagreements on whether Yamina should split, while others referred to it as a \"technical\" matter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/ahead-of-yamina-split-smotrich-calls-for-religious-slates-to-stick-together/|title=Ahead of Yamina split, Smotrich calls for religious slates to stick together|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|date=7 October 2019|author=Jacob Magid}}</ref> The alliance did split on 10 October 2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/yamina-party-officially-splits-into-new-right-jewish-home-national-union/|title=Yamina party officially splits into New Right, Jewish Home-National Union|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|date=10 October 2019|author=Raoul Wootliff}}</ref> and re-formed on 15 January 2020 in the run-up to the [[2020 Israeli legislative election]].<ref name=as15jan/>\n\n==Background==\nOn 21 July 2019, after not making it past the electoral threshold in the [[April 2019 Israeli legislative election]], New Right leader [[Naftali Bennett]] decided to give leadership of the party to [[Ayelet Shaked]]. In her opening leadership speech, Shaked declared that she will seek to unite with the Union of Right-Wing Parties (URWP) and other right-wing parties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/taking-reins-from-bennett-shaked-urges-right-wing-slates-to-unite-beneath-her/|title=Taking reins from Bennett, Shaked urges right-wing slates to unite beneath her|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|access-date=15 January 2019|date=21 July 2019|author=Jacob Magid}}</ref>\n\nThe following day, negotiations with the URWP began. The negotiations initially stalled, as URWP leader [[Rafi Peretz]] was unwilling to concede leadership of the list to Shaked, and disagreements arose over how many spots each of the three involved parties would receive on the list. Another subject that arose in the negotiations was whether the radical former URWP member [[Otzma Yehudit]] should be included in the new joint list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/extremist-otzma-yehudit-still-seeking-merger-with-united-right-as-deadline-nears/|title=Extremist Otzma Yehudit still seeking merger with United Right as deadline nears|website=Times of Israel|language=en|access-date=5 August 2019|date=1 August 2019|author=Raoul Wootliff}}</ref>\n\n[[Sara Netanyahu]] (the wife of the prime minister) was recorded speaking with Rafi Peretz' wife, Michal Peretz, in an attempt to convince Peretz to retain his number one slot on the list; she was unsuccessful. It was also revealed that [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] was involved (despite his denial).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/leaked-recordings-reveal-sara-netanyahus-efforts-to-sabotage-urwp-shaked-merger/|title=Leaked recordings reveal Sara Netanyahu\u2019s efforts to sabotage URWP-Shaked merger|website=[[The Times of Israel]]|language=en|access-date=29 July 2019|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref> The URWP and the New Right agreed to a joint run on 29 July 2019, with the New Right's [[Ayelet Shaked]] leading the joint list. As part of the agreement, the alliance declared that they would negotiate together to establish a right-wing government under Benjamin Netanyahu.<ref name = UR1>{{Cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/266645|title=New Right, United Right reach final agreement on joint run|website=Arutz Sheva|language=en|access-date=29 July 2019|date=29 July 2019|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2| Name\n! Ideology\n! Position\n! Leader\n! [[Knesset|Current MKs]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{New Right (Israel)/meta/color}}\"|\n| style=\"width:200px\" | [[New Right (Israel)|New Right]]\n| style=\"width:250px\" | [[National conservatism]], [[Economic liberalism]]\n| style=\"width:100px\" | [[Right-wing politics|Right-wing]]\n| style=\"width:150px\" | [[Naftali Bennett]]\n| {{Composition bar|3|120|{{New Right (Israel)/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Tkuma (political party)/meta/color}}\"|\n| style=\"width:200px\" | [[Tkuma (political party)|National Union]]\n| style=\"width:250px\" | [[Religious Zionism]], [[Ultranationalism]]\n| style=\"width:150px\" | [[Far-right politics|Far-right]]\n| style=\"width:150px\" | [[Bezalel Smotrich]]\n| {{Composition bar|2|120|{{Tkuma (political party)/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{The Jewish Home/meta/color}}\"|\n| style=\"width:200px\" | [[The Jewish Home]]\n| style=\"width:250px\" | [[Religious Zionism]], [[Religious conservatism]]\n| style=\"width:150px\" | [[Right-wing politics|Right-wing]] to [[Far-right politics|Far-right]]\n| style=\"width:150px\" | [[Rafi Peretz]]\n| {{Composition bar|1|120|{{The Jewish Home/meta/color}}}}\n|}\n\n==Principles==\nParty leader Ayelet Shaked listed 11 principles that the Yamina list is determined to uphold:<ref name = URP>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/ayelet.benshaul.shaked/posts/2275277012590712|title=\u05d0\u05e0\u05d7\u05e0\u05d5 \u05d1\u05d9\u05de\u05d9\u05df \u05d4\u05de\u05d0\u05d5\u05d7\u05d3 \u05de\u05d7\u05d5\u05d9\u05d1\u05d9\u05dd, \u05d1\u05e8\u05d0\u05e9 \u05d5\u05d1\u05e8\u05d0\u05e9\u05d5\u05e0\u05d4, \u05dc\u05e6\u05d9\u05d1\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d1\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc \u05d5\u05dc\u05e2\u05e8\u05db\u05d9 \u05d4\u05d9\u05de\u05d9\u05df.|website=Facebook|language=he|access-date=5 August 2019|date=8 August 2019|author=Ayelet Shaked}}</ref>\n#'''Jewish Identity:''' We will work to strengthen the [[Jewish identity]] of the [[State of Israel]], and to strengthen the connection of Israeli students to the [[Torah]], the [[Land of Israel]] and Jewish heritage.\n#'''Nationality:''' We will act for the implementation of the [[Basic Law: Israel as the Nation-State of the Jewish People|Nation-state Law]] and prevention of any harm to it, while continuing to ensure individual rights and equality for all Israeli citizens.\n#'''Unity of the land:''' We are the only party that opposes the establishment of a [[Palestinian state]] and any withdrawal from the territories of the Land of Israel. We will work to develop [[Israeli settlements|settlements]] throughout the country.\n#'''Sovereignty:''' We will act for the full and equitable application of [[national sovereignty]] and the [[rule of law]] to all citizens and residents of Israel, including the end of the [[Israeli Civil Administration|military administration of Judea and Samaria]] and the application of Israeli sovereignty to the territories of [[Judea]], [[Samaria]] and the [[Jordan Valley]].\n#'''Determination against terror''': We will defeat [[terrorism]] with determination and without compromise, we will defeat [[Gaza Strip|Gaza]] border terrorism and end the allowances paid to terrorists by the [[Palestinian Authority]]. We will bring back the corpses of [[Israeli Defense Force|IDF]] soldiers and charge a price from [[Hamas]] for its actions, with total resistance to the release of imprisoned terrorists. We will act to assist disabled IDF veterans and the victims of the conflict.\n#'''Aliyah:''' We will work towards the implementation of a national [[Aliyah]] policy, which will promote Jewish immigration and remove unnecessary barriers to immigration. We will prevent illegal immigration of migrant workers to Israel and prevent the abuse of family reunification policies.\n#'''Competition and liberty:''' We will promote competition to break up [[monopolies]] and [[cartels]], open the economy to international competition and reduce [[central planning]] in the economy. We will promote competition in the housing market, release land for construction, and implement taxation policies that will spur development. We will streamline regulation, reduce the regulatory burden on employers which will encourage employment and productivity, and create a comfortable environment for a [[sharing economy]] and the [[high tech]] industry.\n#'''Right to work:''' We will reform the labor law so unions can only represent all workers in a workplace if they have a majority of its workers unionized, we will implement mandatory government arbitration to solve labor disputes in essential government services and increase transparency in labor organizations.\n#'''Governability:''' We will strengthen the values of governability and democracy. We will strengthen the status of the [[Knesset]] as a legislative authority and restore confidence in the [[Supreme Court of Israel|Supreme Court]] as the judicial authority, in accordance with the law. We will strengthen the status of elected officials in the face of the un-elected bureaucracy.\n#'''Social responsibility:''' We will enact economic and medical protection for the disabled and the elderly, while integrating people with disabilities in education, society and the labor market.\n#'''Galilee and the Negev:''' We will strengthen [[the Galilee]] and [[the Negev]] with additional employment opportunities, housing, health care, tourism, culture, and transport. We will encourage capital investment and private initiatives that will strengthen human capital and allow families to settle and remain in the Galilee and the Negev. We will strengthen [[agriculture]] and the [[Kibbutz|Labor settlements]].\n\nAlongside these united principles, each party retains its own independent platform. Thus, the New Right represents the more \"liberal\" Religious and Secular right, The Jewish Home represents \"mainstream\" [[Religious Zionism]], while Tkuma represents the more nationalist and [[Chardal]] Religious Zionists.\n\n==Candidate list ==\nYamina has six members in the 23rd Knesset.<ref name=as15jan/>\n\n{{Color box|{{New Right (Israel)/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} - [[New Right (Israel)|New Right]], {{Color box|{{The Jewish Home/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} - [[The Jewish Home]], {{Color box|{{Tkuma (political party)/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} - [[Tkuma (political party)|National Union]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! \n! #\n! Name\n! Notes\n|-\n| style=\"background: {{New Right (Israel)/meta/color}}; color: white\" | \n| 1\n| [[Naftali Bennett]]\n| Former head of the New Right and the Jewish Home, and current [[Ministry of Defense (Israel)|Minister of Defence]]\n|-\n| style=\"background: {{The Jewish Home/meta/color}}; color: white\" | \n| 2\n| Rabbi [[Rafi Peretz]]\n| Head of [[The Jewish Home]]. [[Ministry of Education (Israel)|Minister of Education]] and former chief of the [[Military Rabbinate]] \n|-\n| style=\"background: {{New Right (Israel)/meta/color}}; color: white\" | \n| 3\n| [[Ayelet Shaked]]\n| Party leader and head of the [[New Right (Israel)|New Right]]. Former [[Ministry of Justice (Israel)|Minister of Justice]] \n|-\n| style=\"background: {{Tkuma (political party)/meta/color}}; color: white\" | \n| 4\n| [[Bezalel Smotrich]]\n| Head of [[Tkuma (political party)|National Union]]. [[Ministry of Transport (Israel)|Minister of Transport]] and co-founder of the [[NGO]] [[Regavim (NGO)|Regavim]]\n|-\n| style=\"background: {{New Right (Israel)/meta/color}}; color: white\" | \n| 5\n| Colonel (Res.) [[Matan Kahana]]\n| Former [[Sayeret Matkal]] officer and [[F-16]] Squadron Commander\n|-\n| style=\"background: {{Tkuma (political party)/meta/color}}; color: white\" | \n| 6\n| [[Ofir Sofer]] \n| National Union Secretary General\n|}\n\n== Leaders ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! colspan=\"3\" | Leader\n! Took office\n! Left office\n|-\n| style=\"background: #CAD93B; color: white\" | \n| [[File:AYELET SHAKED.jpg|70px]]\n| [[Ayelet Shaked]]\n| 2019\n| 2019\n|-\n| style=\"background: #CAD93B; color: white\" | \n| [[File:Naftali Bennett.jpg|70px]]\n| [[Naftali Bennett]]\n| 2020\n| Present\n|}\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Election year\n! Party Leader\n! # of overall votes\n! % of overall vote\n! # of overall seats<br/>won\n! +/-\n! Gov?\n|-\n! [[September 2019 Israeli legislative election|September 2019]]\n| [[Ayelet Shaked]]\n| 260,655\n| 5.87\n| {{Composition bar|7|120|hex=#CAD93B}}\n| {{increase}} 1\n| {{Maybe|Snap election}}\n|-\n! [[2020 Israeli legislative election|2020]]\n| [[Naftali Bennett]]\n| 240,162\n| 5.25\n| {{Composition bar|6|120|hex=#CAD93B}}\n| {{decrease}} 1\n| TBD\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Official website}} {{in lang|he}}\n{{Israeli political parties}}\n\n[[Category:Political party alliances in Israel]]\n[[Category:Orthodox Jewish political parties]]\n[[Category:Conservative parties in Israel]]\n[[Category:Social conservative parties]]\n[[Category:Religious Zionist political parties in Israel]]\n[[Category:Religious Zionism]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2019]]\n[[Category:2019 disestablishments in Israel]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2020]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Israeli electoral alliance}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Yamina\n| foundation = 29 July 2019 (first time)<br>15 January 2020 (revival)\n| dissolution = 10 October 2019 (first time)\n| country = Israel\n| ideology = [[Zionism]]<br>[[National conservatism]]<br>[[Economic liberalism]]<br>[[Judicial restraint]]<br>[[Israeli settlements|Settler]] interests<br>'''Factions:'''<br>[[Religious conservatism]]<br>[[Religious Zionism]]<br>[[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] interests<br>[[Right-wing populism]]\n| affiliation1 = [[New Right (Israel)| New Right]]<br>[[Tkuma (political party)|National Union]]<br>[[The Jewish Home]]\n| affiliation1_title = Member parties\n| leader = [[Naftali Bennett]]\n| native_name = {{Hebrew|\u05d9\u05de\u05d9\u05e0\u05d4}}\n| logo = File:Yamina logo.svg\n| logo_size = 135px\n| colorcode = {{Yamina/meta/color}}\n| colours = {{Color box|{{Yamina/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|#007DB0|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|#F5711F|border=darkgray}}\n{{Color box|#FFFFFF|border=darkgray}}\n| slogan = Israel wants to go right.\n| seats1_title = [[Knesset]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|6|120|hex={{Yamina/meta/color}}}}\n| symbol = {{hebrew|\u05d8\u05d1}}\n| position = [[Right-wing]] to [[Far-right politics|far-right]]\n| website = {{URL|https://yemina.co.il}}\n| headquarters =\n}}\n\n'''Yamina''' ({{Lang-he-n|\u05d9\u05de\u05d9\u05e0\u05d4}}, lit. ''Rightwards'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/267286|title=United Right to run under name 'Yemina'|work=[[Arutz Sheva]]|date=12 August 2019|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref> is an Israeli [[political alliance]] of [[right-wing]] to [[far-right]] parties, that was originally configured as the [[New Right (Israel)|New Right]] and the [[Union of Right-Wing Parties]] (a union of [[The Jewish Home]] and [[Tkuma (political party)|Tkuma]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/New-Right-and-URP-seal-political-union-deal-597080|title=Right-wing parties form alliance to be led by Shaked |work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |date=30 July 2019 |author=Jeremy Sharon}}</ref> The current incarnation of the alliance includes the [[New Right (Israel)|New Right]], The Jewish Home and Tkuma.<ref name=as15jan>{{cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/274617|title=Bennett, Peretz, Smotrich agree to joint run without Ben Gvir|work=[[Arutz Sheva]]|author=[[Staff writer]]|date=15 January 2020|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe list was created ahead of the [[September 2019 Israeli legislative election]], in which Yamina secured seven seats in the Knesset.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel-Elections/Israel-elections-results-based-on-counted-ballots-12-am-602045 |title=95% of votes counted: 33 seats for Blue & White, 32 for Likud |work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |date=18 September 2019}}</ref> The alliance was expected to split on 6 October, with the New Right as its own faction while Tkuma and the Jewish Home will stay together, though the alliance continued to negotiate as a single bloc in the aftermath of the election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Yamina-to-officially-split-on-Sunday-603705|title=Yamina to officially split on Sunday |work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=4 October 2019}}</ref> The meeting on 6 October was postponed, with some citing disagreements on whether Yamina should split, while others referred to it as a \"technical\" matter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/ahead-of-yamina-split-smotrich-calls-for-religious-slates-to-stick-together/|title=Ahead of Yamina split, Smotrich calls for religious slates to stick together|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|date=7 October 2019|author=Jacob Magid}}</ref> The alliance did split on 10 October 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/yamina-party-officially-splits-into-new-right-jewish-home-national-union/|title=Yamina party officially splits into New Right, Jewish Home-National Union|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|date=10 October 2019|author=Raoul Wootliff}}</ref>, and re-formed on 15 January 2020 in the run-up to the [[2020 Israeli legislative election]].<ref name=as15jan/>\n\n==Background==\nOn 21 July 2019, after not making it past the electoral threshold in the [[April 2019 Israeli legislative election]], New Right leader [[Naftali Bennett]] decided to give leadership of the party to [[Ayelet Shaked]]. In her opening leadership speech, Shaked declared that she will seek to unite with the Union of Right-Wing Parties (URWP) and other right-wing parties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/taking-reins-from-bennett-shaked-urges-right-wing-slates-to-unite-beneath-her/|title=Taking reins from Bennett, Shaked urges right-wing slates to unite beneath her|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|access-date=15 January 2019|date=21 July 2019|author=Jacob Magid}}</ref>\n\nThe following day, negotiations with the URWP began. The negotiations initially stalled, as URWP leader [[Rafi Peretz]] was unwilling to concede leadership of the list to Shaked, and disagreements arose over how many spots each of the three involved parties would receive on the list. Another subject that arose in the negotiations was whether the radical former URWP member [[Otzma Yehudit]] should be included in the new joint list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/extremist-otzma-yehudit-still-seeking-merger-with-united-right-as-deadline-nears/|title=Extremist Otzma Yehudit still seeking merger with United Right as deadline nears|website=Times of Israel|language=en|access-date=5 August 2019|date=1 August 2019|author=Raoul Wootliff}}</ref> \n\n[[Sara Netanyahu]] (the wife of the prime minister) was recorded speaking with Rafi Peretz' wife, Michal Peretz, in an attempt to convince Peretz to retain his number one slot on the list; she was unsuccessful. It was also revealed that [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] was involved (despite his denial).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/leaked-recordings-reveal-sara-netanyahus-efforts-to-sabotage-urwp-shaked-merger/|title=Leaked recordings reveal Sara Netanyahu\u2019s efforts to sabotage URWP-Shaked merger|website=[[The Times of Israel]]|language=en|access-date=29 July 2019|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref> The URWP and the New Right agreed to a joint run on 29 July 2019, with the New Right's [[Ayelet Shaked]] leading the joint list. As part of the agreement, the alliance declared that they would negotiate together to establish a right-wing government under Benjamin Netanyahu.<ref name = UR1>{{Cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/266645|title=New Right, United Right reach final agreement on joint run|website=Arutz Sheva|language=en|access-date=29 July 2019|date=29 July 2019|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2| Name\n! Ideology\n! Position\n! Leader\n! [[Knesset|Current MKs]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{New Right (Israel)/meta/color}}\"|\n| style=\"width:200px\" | [[New Right (Israel)|New Right]]\n| style=\"width:250px\" | [[National conservatism]], [[Economic liberalism]]\n| style=\"width:100px\" | [[Right-wing politics|Right-wing]]\n| style=\"width:150px\" | [[Naftali Bennett]]\n| {{Composition bar|3|120|{{New Right (Israel)/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Tkuma (political party)/meta/color}}\"|\n| style=\"width:200px\" | [[Tkuma (political party)|National Union]]\n| style=\"width:250px\" | [[Religious Zionism]], [[Ultranationalism]]\n| style=\"width:150px\" | [[Far-right politics|Far-right]]\n| style=\"width:150px\" | [[Bezalel Smotrich]]\n| {{Composition bar|2|120|{{Tkuma (political party)/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{The Jewish Home/meta/color}}\"|\n| style=\"width:200px\" | [[The Jewish Home]]\n| style=\"width:250px\" | [[Religious Zionism]], [[Religious conservatism]]\n| style=\"width:150px\" | [[Right-wing politics|Right-wing]] to [[Far-right politics|Far-right]]\n| style=\"width:150px\" | [[Rafi Peretz]]\n| {{Composition bar|1|120|{{The Jewish Home/meta/color}}}}\n|}\n\n==Principles==\nParty leader Ayelet Shaked listed 11 principles that the Yamina list is determined to uphold:<ref name = URP>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/ayelet.benshaul.shaked/posts/2275277012590712|title=\u05d0\u05e0\u05d7\u05e0\u05d5 \u05d1\u05d9\u05de\u05d9\u05df \u05d4\u05de\u05d0\u05d5\u05d7\u05d3 \u05de\u05d7\u05d5\u05d9\u05d1\u05d9\u05dd, \u05d1\u05e8\u05d0\u05e9 \u05d5\u05d1\u05e8\u05d0\u05e9\u05d5\u05e0\u05d4, \u05dc\u05e6\u05d9\u05d1\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d1\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc \u05d5\u05dc\u05e2\u05e8\u05db\u05d9 \u05d4\u05d9\u05de\u05d9\u05df.|website=Facebook|language=he|access-date=5 August 2019|date=8 August 2019|author=Ayelet Shaked}}</ref>\n#'''Jewish Identity:''' We will work to strengthen the [[Jewish identity]] of the [[State of Israel]], and to strengthen the connection of Israeli students to the [[Torah]], the [[Land of Israel]] and Jewish heritage.\n#'''Nationality:''' We will act for the implementation of the [[Basic Law: Israel as the Nation-State of the Jewish People|Nation-state Law]] and prevention of any harm to it, while continuing to ensure individual rights and equality for all Israeli citizens.\n#'''Unity of the land:''' We are the only party that opposes the establishment of a [[Palestinian state]] and any withdrawal from the territories of the Land of Israel. We will work to develop [[Israeli settlements|settlements]] throughout the country.\n#'''Sovereignty:''' We will act for the full and equitable application of [[national sovereignty]] and the [[rule of law]] to all citizens and residents of Israel, including the end of the [[Israeli Civil Administration |military administration of Judea and Samaria]] and the application of Israeli sovereignty to the territories of [[Judea]], [[Samaria]] and the [[Jordan Valley]].\n#'''Determination against terror''': We will defeat [[terrorism]] with determination and without compromise, we will defeat [[Gaza Strip|Gaza]] border terrorism and end the allowances payed to terrorists by the [[Palestinian Authority]]. We will bring back the corpses of [[Israeli Defense Force|IDF]] soldiers and charge a price from [[Hamas]] for its actions, with total resistance to the release of imprisoned terrorists. We will act to assist disabled IDF veterans and the victims of the conflict.\n#'''Aliyah:''' We will work towards the implementation of a national [[Aliyah]] policy, which will promote Jewish immigration and remove unnecessary barriers to immigration. We will prevent illegal immigration of migrant workers to Israel and prevent the abuse of family reunification policies.\n#'''Competition and liberty:''' We will promote competition to break up [[monopolies]] and [[cartels]], open the economy to international competition and reduce [[central planning]] in the economy. We will promote competition in the housing market, release land for construction, and implement taxation policies that will spur development. We will streamline regulation, reduce the regulatory burden on employers which will encourage employment and productivity, and create a comfortable environment for a [[sharing economy]] and the [[high tech]] industry.\n#'''Right to work:''' We will reform the labor law so unions can only represent all workers in a workplace if they have a majority of its workers unionized, we will implement mandatory government arbitration to solve labor disputes in essential government services and increase transparency in labor organizations.\n#'''Governability:''' We will strengthen the values of governability and democracy. We will strengthen the status of the [[Knesset]] as a legislative authority and restore confidence in the [[Supreme Court of Israel| Supreme Court]] as the judicial authority, in accordance with the law. We will strengthen the status of elected officials in the face of the un-elected bureaucracy.\n#'''Social responsibility:''' We will enact economic and medical protection for the disabled and the elderly, while integrating people with disabilities in education, society and the labor market.\n#'''Galilee and the Negev:''' We will strengthen [[the Galilee]] and [[the Negev]] with additional employment opportunities, housing, health care, tourism, culture, and transport. We will encourage capital investment and private initiatives that will strengthen human capital and allow families to settle and remain in the Galilee and the Negev. We will strengthen [[agriculture]] and the [[Kibbutz|Labor settlements]].\n\nAlongside these united principles, each party retains its own independent platform. Thus, the New Right represents the more \"liberal\" Religious and Secular right, The Jewish Home represents \"mainstream\" [[Religious Zionism]], while Tkuma represents the more nationalist and [[Chardal]] Religious Zionists.\n\n==Candidate list ==\nYamina has six members in the 23rd Knesset.<ref name=as15jan/>\n\n{{Color box|{{New Right (Israel)/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} - [[New Right (Israel)|New Right]], {{Color box|{{The Jewish Home/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} - [[The Jewish Home]], {{Color box|{{Tkuma (political party)/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} - [[Tkuma (political party)|National Union]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! \n! #\n! Name\n! Notes\n|-\n| style=\"background: {{New Right (Israel)/meta/color}}; color: white\" | \n| 1\n| [[Naftali Bennett]]\n| Former head of the New Right and the Jewish Home, and current [[Ministry of Defense (Israel)| Minister of Defence]]\n|-\n| style=\"background: {{The Jewish Home/meta/color}}; color: white\" | \n| 2\n| Rabbi [[Rafi Peretz]]\n| Head of [[The Jewish Home]]. [[Ministry of Education (Israel)|Minister of Education]] and former chief of the [[Military Rabbinate]] \n|-\n| style=\"background: {{New Right (Israel)/meta/color}}; color: white\" | \n| 3\n| [[Ayelet Shaked]]\n| Party leader and head of the [[New Right (Israel)|New Right]]. Former [[Ministry of Justice (Israel)|Minister of Justice]] \n|-\n| style=\"background: {{Tkuma (political party)/meta/color}}; color: white\" | \n| 4\n| [[Bezalel Smotrich]]\n| Head of [[Tkuma (political party)|National Union]]. [[Ministry of Transport (Israel)|Minister of Transport]] and co-founder of the [[NGO]] [[Regavim (NGO)|Regavim]]\n|-\n| style=\"background: {{New Right (Israel)/meta/color}}; color: white\" | \n| 5\n| Colonel (Res.) [[Matan Kahana]]\n| Former [[Sayeret Matkal]] officer and [[F-16]] Squadron Commander\n|-\n| style=\"background: {{Tkuma (political party)/meta/color}}; color: white\" | \n| 6\n| [[Ofir Sofer]] \n| National Union Secretary General\n|}\n\n== Leaders ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! colspan=\"3\" | Leader\n! Took office\n! Left office\n|-\n| style=\"background: #CAD93B; color: white\" | \n| [[File:AYELET SHAKED.jpg|70px]]\n| [[Ayelet Shaked]]\n| 2019\n| 2019\n|-\n| style=\"background: #CAD93B; color: white\" | \n| [[File:Naftali Bennett.jpg|70px]]\n| [[Naftali Bennett]]\n| 2020\n| Present\n|}\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Election year\n! Party Leader\n! # of overall votes\n! % of overall vote\n! # of overall seats<br/>won\n! +/-\n! Gov?\n|-\n! [[September 2019 Israeli legislative election|September 2019]]\n| [[Ayelet Shaked]]\n| 260,655\n| 5.87\n| {{Composition bar|7|120|hex=#CAD93B}}\n| {{increase}} 1\n| {{Maybe|Snap election}}\n|-\n! [[2020 Israeli legislative election|2020]]\n| [[Naftali Bennett]]\n| 240,162\n| 5.25\n| {{Composition bar|6|120|hex=#CAD93B}}\n| {{decrease}} 1\n| TBD\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Official website}} {{in lang|he}}\n{{Israeli political parties}}\n\n[[Category:Political party alliances in Israel]]\n[[Category:Orthodox Jewish political parties]]\n[[Category:Conservative parties in Israel]]\n[[Category:Social conservative parties]]\n[[Category:Religious Zionist political parties in Israel]]\n[[Category:Religious Zionism]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2019]]\n[[Category:2019 disestablishments in Israel]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2020]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: payed \u2192 paid", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yamina_(political_alliance)"}
{"title_page": "Paralouatta", "text_new": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = [[Burdigalian]]-[[Pleistocene]]<br>~{{fossil range|17|1}}\n| image = Paralouatta marianae skull.jpg\n| image_caption = ''Paralouatta marianae'' skull\n| display_parents = 2\n| taxon = Paralouatta\n| authority = Rivero & Arredondo 1991\n| subdivision_ranks = [[Species]]\n| subdivision  =\n* \u2020''P. marianae'' {{small|MacPhee et al. 2003}}\n* \u2020''P. varonai'' {{small|Rivero & Arredondo 1991}}\n| type_species = '''''Paralouatta varonai'''''\n}}\n\n'''''Paralouatta''''' is a [[platyrrhine]] [[genus]] that currently contains two [[extinct]] species of small [[primate]]s that lived on the island of [[Cuba]].\n\n== Description ==\nThe [[Cuba]]n fossil primate, ''Paralouatta varonai'' was described from a nearly complete [[cranium]] from the late [[Quaternary]] in 1991. This cranium and a number of isolated teeth and postcranial bones were found in the [[Cueva del Mono]], a cave site in [[Pinar del R\u00edo Province]]. The initial description of the cranium included a proposal that ''Paralouatta varonai'' was a close Caribbean relative of the extant ''Alouatta'' ([[howler monkey]]s) of Central and South America,<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Rivero, M.  |author2=Arredondo, O.  |lastauthoramp=yes | year = 1991 | title = ''Paralouatta varonai'', a new Quaternary platyrrhine from Cuba | journal = Journal of Human Evolution | volume = 21 | pages = 1\u201311 | doi = 10.1016/0047-2484(91)90032-Q}}</ref> but this taxonomic placement has been called into question with the analysis of the dental remains.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Horovitz, I.  |author2=MacPhee, R.D.E.  |lastauthoramp=yes | year = 1999 | title = The quaternary Cuban platyrrhine ''Paralouatta varonai'' and the origin of the Antillean monkeys | journal = Journal of Human Evolution| pmid = 9924133 | volume = 36 | issue = 1 | pages = 33\u201368 | doi = 10.1006/jhev.1998.0259}}</ref> Based on shared similarities with the two other Caribbean primates ''[[Xenothrix mcgregori]]'' and ''[[Antillothrix bernensis]]'', MacPhee and Horovitz have proposed that the Caribbean primates are part of a monophyletic radiation which entered the Caribbean at the [[Oligocene]]&ndash;[[Miocene]] boundary. More recent research confirms this assessment and places these three species in the tribe [[Xenotrichini]].<ref>{{cite journal |author1=MacPhee, R.D.E.  |author2=Horovitz, I.  |lastauthoramp=yes | year = 2004 | title = New Craniodental Remains of the Quaternary Jamaican Monkey ''Xenothrix mcgregori'' (Xenotrichini, Callicebinae, Pitheciidae), with a Reconsideration of the ''Aotus'' Hypothesis | journal = American Museum Novitates | volume = 3434 | issue = 1 | pages = 1\u201351 | doi = 10.1206/0003-0082(2004)434<0001:NCROTQ>2.0.CO;2}}</ref>  The postcranial morphology of ''Paralouatta'' suggests that it was partly terrestrial<ref>{{Cite journal|last=P\u00fcschel|first=Thomas A.|last2=Marc\u00e9-Nogu\u00e9|first2=Jordi|last3=Gladman|first3=Justin|last4=Patel|first4=Biren A.|last5=Alm\u00e9cija|first5=Sergio|last6=Sellers|first6=William I.|date=2020|title=Getting Its Feet on the Ground: Elucidating Paralouatta\u2019s Semi-Terrestriality Using the Virtual Morpho-Functional Toolbox|url=https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/feart.2020.00079/full|journal=Frontiers in Earth Science|language=English|volume=8|doi=10.3389/feart.2020.00079|issn=2296-6463}}</ref>, and a likely example of [[island gigantism]].<ref name = \"MacPhee2003\"/>\n\nA second species of ''Paralouatta'' (''P. marianae'') has also been described from the [[Burdigalian]] (~18 million years old) [[Lagunitas Formation, Cuba|Lagunitas Formation]] and is the largest [[Neotropic primate]] known of that epoch.<ref name = \"MacPhee2003\">{{cite journal | title = Domo de Zaza, an Early Miocene Vertebrate Locality in South-Central Cuba, with Notes on the Tectonic Evolution of Puerto Rico and the Mona Passage | author = MacPhee, R.D.E., Iturralde-Vinent, M.A., and Gaffney, E.S. | journal = American Museum Novitates | pages =1\u201342 | volume = 3394 | issue = 1 |date=February 2003 | doi = 10.1206/0003-0082(2003)394<0001:DDZAEM>2.0.CO;2| hdl = 2246/2820 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.helsinki.fi/~mhaaramo/metazoa/deuterostoma/chordata/synapsida/eutheria/primates/platyrrhini/homunculini.html Mikko's Phylogeny archive]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1431061}}\n\n[[Category:Pitheciidae|\u2020Paralouatta]]\n[[Category:Prehistoric monkeys]]\n[[Category:Prehistoric primate genera]]\n[[Category:Burdigalian life]]\n[[Category:Miocene mammals of North America]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene mammals of North America]]\n[[Category:Fossils of Cuba]]\n[[Category:Neogene Cuba]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene Caribbean]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 1991]]\n", "text_old": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = [[Burdigalian]]-[[Pleistocene]]<br>~{{fossil range|17|1}}\n| image = Paralouatta marianae skull.jpg\n| image_caption = ''Paralouatta marianae'' skull\n| display_parents = 2\n| taxon = Paralouatta\n| authority = Rivero & Arredondo 1991\n| subdivision_ranks = [[Species]]\n| subdivision  =\n* \u2020''P. marianae'' {{small|MacPhee et al. 2003}}\n* \u2020''P. varonai'' {{small|Rivero & Arredondo 1991}}\n| type_species = '''''Paralouatta varonai'''''\n}}\n\n'''''Paralouatta''''' is a [[platyrrhine]] [[genus]] that currently contains two [[extinct]] species of small [[primate]]s that lived on the island of [[Cuba]].\n\n== Description ==\nThe [[Cuba]]n fossil primate, ''Paralouatta varonai'' was described from a nearly complete [[cranium]] from the late [[Quaternary]] in 1991. This cranium and a number of isolated teeth and postcranial bones were found in the [[Cueva del Mono]], a cave site in [[Pinar del R\u00edo Province]]. The initial description of the cranium included a proposal that ''Paralouatta varonai'' was a close Caribbean relative of the extant ''Alouatta'' ([[howler monkey]]s) of Central and South America,<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Rivero, M.  |author2=Arredondo, O.  |lastauthoramp=yes | year = 1991 | title = ''Paralouatta varonai'', a new Quaternary platyrrhine from Cuba | journal = Journal of Human Evolution | volume = 21 | pages = 1\u201311 | doi = 10.1016/0047-2484(91)90032-Q}}</ref> but this taxonomic placement has been called into question with the analysis of the dental remains.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Horovitz, I.  |author2=MacPhee, R.D.E.  |lastauthoramp=yes | year = 1999 | title = The quaternary Cuban platyrrhine ''Paralouatta varonai'' and the origin of the Antillean monkeys | journal = Journal of Human Evolution| pmid = 9924133 | volume = 36 | issue = 1 | pages = 33\u201368 | doi = 10.1006/jhev.1998.0259}}</ref> Based on shared similarities with the two other Caribbean primates ''[[Xenothrix mcgregori]]'' and ''[[Antillothrix bernensis]]'', MacPhee and Horovitz have proposed that the Caribbean primates are part of a monophyletic radiation which entered the Caribbean at the [[Oligocene]]&ndash;[[Miocene]] boundary. More recent research confirms this assessment and places these three species in the tribe [[Xenotrichini]].<ref>{{cite journal |author1=MacPhee, R.D.E.  |author2=Horovitz, I.  |lastauthoramp=yes | year = 2004 | title = New Craniodental Remains of the Quaternary Jamaican Monkey ''Xenothrix mcgregori'' (Xenotrichini, Callicebinae, Pitheciidae), with a Reconsideration of the ''Aotus'' Hypothesis | journal = American Museum Novitates | volume = 3434 | issue = 1 | pages = 1\u201351 | doi = 10.1206/0003-0082(2004)434<0001:NCROTQ>2.0.CO;2}}</ref> Limb modifications and its large size suggest it was partly terrestrial, and a likely example of [[island gigantism]].<ref name = \"MacPhee2003\"/>\n\nA second species of ''Paralouatta'' (''P. marianae'') has also been described from the [[Burdigalian]] (~18 million years old) [[Lagunitas Formation, Cuba|Lagunitas Formation]] and is the largest [[Neotropic primate]] known of that epoch.<ref name = \"MacPhee2003\">{{cite journal | title = Domo de Zaza, an Early Miocene Vertebrate Locality in South-Central Cuba, with Notes on the Tectonic Evolution of Puerto Rico and the Mona Passage | author = MacPhee, R.D.E., Iturralde-Vinent, M.A., and Gaffney, E.S. | journal = American Museum Novitates | pages =1\u201342 | volume = 3394 | issue = 1 |date=February 2003 | doi = 10.1206/0003-0082(2003)394<0001:DDZAEM>2.0.CO;2| hdl = 2246/2820 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.helsinki.fi/~mhaaramo/metazoa/deuterostoma/chordata/synapsida/eutheria/primates/platyrrhini/homunculini.html Mikko's Phylogeny archive]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1431061}}\n\n[[Category:Pitheciidae|\u2020Paralouatta]]\n[[Category:Prehistoric monkeys]]\n[[Category:Prehistoric primate genera]]\n[[Category:Burdigalian life]]\n[[Category:Miocene mammals of North America]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene mammals of North America]]\n[[Category:Fossils of Cuba]]\n[[Category:Neogene Cuba]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene Caribbean]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 1991]]\n", "name_user": "ThomPuschel", "label": "safe", "comment": "reference added when referring to the semi-terrestrial locomotion of Paralouatta", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paralouatta"}
{"title_page": "Jon Klassen", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n| name = Jon Klassen\n| honorific-suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|CM}}\n| image = Jon Klassen in 2016.jpg\n| caption = Jon Klassen in 2016.\n| alt = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1981|11|29}}\n| birth_place = [[Winnipeg]], Manitoba, Canada <!-- see TALK#Vital data -->\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| occupation = Illustrator, writer\n| nationality = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| period = 2005\u2013present <!-- includes animation -->\n| genre = [[Children's literature|Children's]] [[picture books]], [[animation]]\n| subject = \n| notableworks = {{plainlist|\n* ''[[Sam and Dave Dig a Hole]]'' &nbsp;(illus.)\n* ''[[I Want My Hat Back]]''\n* ''[[This Is Not My Hat]]''\n}}\n| awards = {{awd |[[Governor General's Award for English-language children's illustration|Governor General's Award]] |2010 }} {{awd |[[Caldecott Medal]] |2013}} {{awd |[[Greenaway Medal]] |2014}}\n}}\n\n'''Jon Klassen''' {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|CM}} (born November 29, 1981)<ref name=EBkids/> is a Canadian writer and illustrator of children's books and an animator. He won both the American [[Caldecott Medal]] and the British [[Kate Greenaway Medal]] for children's book illustration, recognizing the 2012 [[picture book]] ''[[This Is Not My Hat]]'', which he also wrote.<ref name=caldecott/><ref name=pr2013/><ref name=medal2014/><ref name=pr2014/> He is the first person to win both awards for the same work.{{efn|name=twoawards}}\n\n''This Is Not My Hat'' is a companion to Klassen's preceding picture book, ''[[I Want My Hat Back|I&nbsp;Want My Hat Back]]'' (2011), which was his first as both writer and illustrator.<ref name=PW/> Both books were on the [[New York Times Best Seller list]] for more than 40 weeks; by April 2014 one or the other had been translated into 22 languages and they had jointly surpassed one million worldwide sales.<ref name=PW/> Both books were recommended for children ages 5+ by the Greenaway judges.<ref name=short2013/><ref name=short2014/> Klassen's \"hat\" trilogy was completed with the publication of ''[[We Found a Hat]]'' (2016).\n\n==Personal life==\nKlassen was born in [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]], Canada, in 1981 and grew up in [[Niagara Falls]] and [[Toronto]], Ontario.<ref name=EBkids>{{cite web |url= http://kids.britannica.com/comptons/article-9603281/Jon-Klassen |title=Jon Klassen |work=Britannica Online for Kids (kids.eb.com) |accessdate=23 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/canadian-writer-jon-klassen-wins-u-s-children-s-book-prize-1.1409756 |title=Canadian writer Jon Klassen wins U.S. children's book prize |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=28 January 2013  |accessdate=23 November 2013}}</ref> He studied animation<ref name=imundo>{{cite web|url=http://www.illustrationmundo.com/wp/417|title=Interview with Jon Klassen|last=Williams|first=Nate |publisher=Illustration Mundo (illustrationmundo.com) |accessdate=2 January 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090129125142/http://www.illustrationmundo.com/wp/417 |date=31 December 2008 |archivedate=2009-01-29}}</ref> at [[Sheridan College]], graduated in 2005,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sheridancollege.ca/Alumni/Alumni%20Profile%20Archives/Animation%20Arts%20and%20Design/Jon%20Klassen.aspx|title=Jon Klassen: Bringing Stories to Life|publisher=[[Sheridan College]]|accessdate=2 January 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111016084116/http://sheridancollege.ca/Alumni/Alumni%20Profile%20Archives/Animation%20Arts%20and%20Design/Jon%20Klassen.aspx |archivedate=2011-10-16}}</ref> and moved to [[Los Angeles]].<!--one source is Candlewick--><ref name=pr2013/>\n\nThat year<!--YouTube upload 2005-12-05--> he made an animated short with Daniel Rodrigues, ''An Eye for Annai''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ecrans.fr/Vu-sur-le-www,4775.html|title=Vu sur le www: Des canards, un \u0153il, etc.|date=4 August 2008| newspaper=[[Lib\u00e9ration]]: Ecrans |language=French |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/28/AR2007062802722.html|title=Child's Play|date=1 July 2007| newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> He worked on animation of the feature films ''[[Kung Fu Panda]]'' (2008)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.julienews.it/notizia/cultura-e-tempo-libero/a-sarmede-jon-klassen-illustratore-di-kung-fu-panda/84474_cultura-e-tempo-libero_7.html |title=A Sarmede Jon Klassen: illustratore di Kung Fu Panda |language=Italian |date=4 August 2011 |work=Cultura e Tempo Libero |publisher=JulieNews.it |accessdate=2 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508005534/http://www.julienews.it/notizia/cultura-e-tempo-libero/a-sarmede-jon-klassen-illustratore-di-kung-fu-panda/84474_cultura-e-tempo-libero_7.html |archive-date=8 May 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and ''[[Coraline (film)|Coraline]]'' (2009)<ref name=quill/> and he was art director for the 2009 animated music video of \"[[I'll Go Crazy If I Don't Go Crazy Tonight#Music videos|I'll Go Crazy If I Don't Go Crazy Tonight]]\" by U2.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&aid=73&rid=4282361&tpl=archnews&only=1|title=Irish Animator David O'Reilly Directs Latest U2 Video|date=24 July 2009|publisher=[[Irish Film and Television Network]]|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://broadwayworld.com/article/Sofa_Snark_U2_Goes_Crazy_For_Animation_20090723|title=Sofa Snark: U2 Goes 'Crazy' For Animation|last=Sims|first=James|date=23 July 2009|publisher=Broadwayworld.com|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nKlassen told Illustration Mundo at the end of 2008, \"I work at an animation studio right now on things that won't come out for years and years. ...&nbsp; it can sometimes feel like the equivalent of emptying a glass of water into a lake.\"<ref name=imundo/>\n\n==Career== <!-- \"Career\" evidently meaning books, perhaps all children's books -->\n\nIn 2010, Klassen achieved international recognition when he was awarded the [[Governor General's Award for English-language children's illustration]] for his work on the picture book ''Cats' Night Out'', written by Carolyn Stutson.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/arts-and-life/entertainment/arts/gg-literary-award-winners-stunned-overwhelmed-108625109.html|title=GG Literary Award winners 'stunned,' 'overwhelmed'|last=Wyatt|first=Nelson|date=17 November 2010 |newspaper=[[Winnipeg Free Press]] |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> He also illustrated ''The Mysterious Howling'' by Maryrose Wood, the first novel in a HarperCollins series called ''The Incorrigible Children of Ashton Place'' along with the second and third, and the first edition hardcover of the fourth novel in the series.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/11/books/review/Bookshelf-t.html|title=Children's Books; Bookshelf|last=Just|first=Julie|date=11 April 2010|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |page=BR15 |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref>{{efn|Klassen also illustrated the first two ''Incorrigible Children'' sequels, published in 2011 and 2012. Another illustrator, Eliza Wheeler, handled the paperback version of the fourth novel along with every version of the novels that were published after.}}\n\nHis first solo picture book was ''I Want My Hat Back'', published by [[Candlewick Press]] in September 2011. It features a bear looking for his hat, who finally and off-page eats the rabbit who stole it.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blog.schoollibraryjournal.com/afuse8production/2011/05/28/review-of-the-day-i-want-my-hat-back-by-jon-klassen/|title=Review of the Day: I Want My Hat Back by Jon Klassen |work=A Fuse #8 Production|last=Bird|first=Elizabeth|date=28 May 2011| publisher=[[School Library Journal]] |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]'' named it one of the \"10 Best Illustrated Children's Books for 2011\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/11/03/the-2011-best-illustrated-books/|title=The 2011 Best Illustrated Children's Books|last=Paul|first=Pamela|date=3 November 2011| newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> The book was published in September by Candlewick Press.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wired.com/geekdad/2011/09/picture-book-perfect-i-want-my-hat-back/ |title=Picture (Book) Perfect: I Want My Hat Back | website=Wired.com |last=Liu |first=Jonathan |date=20 September 2011 |accessdate=2 January 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131205114952/http://www.wired.com/geekdad/2011/09/picture-book-perfect-i-want-my-hat-back |archivedate=2013-12-05}}</ref> Klassen said of the ending, which has been called a \"subversive risk\", that \"there was no other way for it to end\". It achieved considerable commercial success, and even became an [[internet meme]] when people started \"posting their own versions of the story\".<ref name=quill>{{cite news|url=http://www.quillandquire.com/blog/index.php/2011/12/19/canadian-illustrator-jon-klassen-finds-success-with-i-want-my-hat-back/|title=Canadian illustrator Jon Klassen finds success with I Want My Hat Back|last=Flinn|first=Sue Carter|date=19 December 2011| publisher=[[Quill & Quire]] |accessdate=2 January 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527223505/http://www.quillandquire.com/blog/index.php/2011/12/19/canadian-illustrator-jon-klassen-finds-success-with-i-want-my-hat-back |archivedate=2013-05-27}}</ref> Pamela Paul praised the book in review for ''The New York Times'': \"it is a wonderful and astonishing thing, the kind of book that makes child laugh and adult chuckle, and both smile in appreciation&nbsp;... [it is] a charmingly wicked little book and the debut of a promising writer-illustrator talent.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/13/books/review/not-just-another-bear-story.html?_r=1&scp=2&sq=jon%20klassen&st=cse|title=Children's Books; Not Just Another Bear Story|last=Paul|first=Pamela|date=13 October 2011| newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> According to the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', \"the joy of this book lies in figuring out the explicit plot from the implicit details in the pictures.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/books/ct-books-hat-back-klassen,0,4024605.story|title='I Want My Hat Back' by Jon Klassen|last=Russell|first=Mary Harris| newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> There has been some discussion of the ending, however: is it appropriate in a children's book that one character kills another without repercussion? A bookseller, who \"need[ed] to go on record as saying I LOVE this book\", reported that some customers love it until they turn the last pages.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.publishersweekly.com/blogs/shelftalker/?p=6170|title=Should the Bear Eat the Rabbit?|last=Leavitt|first=Josie|date=September 2011| newspaper=[[Publishers Weekly]]|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> It was a runner-up for the American [[Geisel Award]] (books for beginning readers)<ref name=geisel>{{cite web |title= (Theodor Seuss) Geisel Award winners and honor books, 2006\u2013present |publisher= ALSC. ALA |url= http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/alsc/awardsgrants/bookmedia/geiselaward/geiselawardpastwinners/index.cfm |accessdate= 1 July 2014}}</ref> and made the Greenaway shortlist.<ref name=short2013/>\n\nKlassen modified the story in a companion book one year later, ''This Is Not My Hat'' (Candlewick, 2012). It features a little fish who steals and wears the hat of a big fish, whom the little one evades until the last pages. Finally the big fish swims back into the book, wearing the hat, with no sign of the thief. This one won the Caldecott and Greenaway Medals, from the American and British professional librarians respectively.<ref name=caldecott/><ref name=medal2014/>{{efn|name=twoawards}} According to the award committee, \"With minute changes in eyes and the slightest displacement of seagrass, Klassen's masterful illustrations tell the story the narrator doesn't know.\"<ref name=pr2013/>{{efn|Klassen also earned one of five Caldecott Honor in 2013 as the illustrator of ''Extra Yarn'', written by [[Mac Barnett]]. Only [[Leonard Weisgard]] previously illustrated two books honored in one year, 1947.}} Klassen was also awarded with a Caldecot Honor that same year for [[Extra Yarn]], only the second time that has happened.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/alsc/2013-caldecott-medal-and-honor-books|title=2013 Caldecott Medal and Honor Books|website=Association for Library Service to Children (ALSC)|language=en|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hbook.com/2013/01/blogs/calling-caldecott/caldecott-2013-post-mortem/|title=Caldecott 2013 post mortem \u2014 The Horn Book|last=Robinson|first=Lolly|date=2013-01-29|website=www.hbook.com|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> The Greenaway recognizes \"distinguished illustration in a book for children\", not necessarily a picture book. According to the British judges, \"The format and layout work perfectly to convey the underwater location with the movement of the action flowing with the water from left to right.&nbsp;... The juxtaposition of text and image works with perfect comic timing. Amazing expression is conveyed by the eyes and dramatic tension by little bubbles.\"<ref name=short2014/> The Greenaway is paired in a London announcement and presentation ceremony with the Carnegie Medal for children's literature, which recognized a controversially grim young-adult novel in 2014. According to the press release, \"both winners independently argued that children benefit from stories without happy endings.\"<ref name=pr2014/> Klassen said in his acceptance speech, \"Making a book, you're kind of going out on a limb in the belief that what you think of as a satisfying story is the same as what other people think of as a satisfying story. This doesn't mean everything in the story turns out alright for everybody, but you, as a storyteller, try and make sure it ends the way the story should end.\"<ref name=pr2014/>\n\nKlassen illustrated ''The Dark'' (2013), written by [[Lemony Snicket]], which made the Greenaway Medal shortlist of eight books alongside ''This Is Not My Hat''.<ref name=short2014/>{{efn|name=twoawards}}{{efn|Other illustrators have recently placed two books on the Greenaway shortlist, in 2008 and 2002.}}He teamed up with Mac Barnett again in 2014, on a picture book published by Candlewick, ''Sam and Dave Dig a Hole''.<ref name=PW1>Lodge, Sally (16 January 2014). [http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/childrens/childrens-book-news/article/60678-candlewick-signs-new-mac-barnett-jon-klassen-collaboration.html \"Candlewick Signs New Mac Barnett\u2013Jon Klassen Collaboration\"]. ''Publisher's Weekly''. Retrieved 8 Mar 2014.</ref>\n\nIn 2019, ''I Want My Hat Back'', ''This Is Not My Hat'', and ''We Found a Hat'' were released in a boxed set by Candlewick Press as ''Jon Klassen's Hat Box''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43671840-jon-klassen-s-hat-box|title=Jon Klassen's Hat Box|last=|first=|date=|website=Goodreads|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n<!-- 2014-07-03 intended to be complete for Engl-lang editions of books as writer OR illustrator; Works include contributions to film animation, none yet listed here. -->\n\n;Books written and illustrated\n* ''[[I Want My Hat Back]]'', by Klassen (Candlewick Press, Sep 2011) {{ISBN|9780763655983}}\n* ''[[This Is Not My Hat]]'', by Klassen (Candlewick, Oct 2012) {{ISBN|9780763655990}}\n* ''[[We Found a Hat]]'', by Klassen (Candlewick, Oct 2016) {{ISBN|9780763656003}}\n\n;With [[Mac Barnett]]\n*The Shape Trilogy\n** ''Triangle'' (Candlewick, Mar 2017), {{ISBN|9780763696030}}\n** ''Square'' (May 2018) {{ISBN|978-1406378658}}\n** ''Circle'' (Candlewick, March, 2019) {{ISBN|978-0763696085}}\n\n* ''Extra Yarn'', by Mac Barnett (Balzer + Bray, a [[HarperCollins]] imprint, Jan 2012) {{ISBN|9780061953385}}\n* ''[[Sam and Dave Dig a Hole]]'', by Barnett (Candlewick, Oct 2014), {{ISBN|9780763662295}}\n* ''The Wolf, the Duck, and the Mouse'', by Mac Barnett (Candlewick, Oct 2017), {{ISBN|9780763677541}}\n\n;Children's picture books illustrated\n* ''Cats' Night Out'', by Carolyn Stutson (Simon & Schuster, Mar 2010), {{ISBN|9781416940050}}\n* ''House Held Up By Trees'', by [[Ted Kooser]] (Candlewick, Mar 2012), {{ISBN|9780763651077}}\n* ''The Dark'', by [[Lemony Snicket]] ([[Little, Brown]], Apr 2013), {{ISBN|9780316187480}}\n\n;Other books illustrated\n* ''The Incorrigible Children of Ashton Place'' \u2013 series of novels by Maryrose Wood (published by Balzer + Bray)\n** Book I: ''The Mysterious Howling'' (Feb 2010), {{ISBN|9780061791055}}\n** Book II: ''The Hidden Gallery'' (Feb 2011), {{ISBN|9780061791123}}\n** Book III: ''The Unseen Guest'' (Mar 2012), {{ISBN|9780061791185}}\n** Book IV: ''The Interrupted Tale'' (Dec 2013), {{ISBN|9780061791222}}\n: (Book V: ''The Unmapped Sea'' (Apr 2015), {{ISBN|9780062110411}}, was illustrated by [[Eliza Wheeler]])\n* ''Vanished'', by Sheela Chari (Hyperion, July 2011), {{ISBN|9781423131632}}\n* ''The Watch that Ends the Night: Voices from the Titanic'', by Allan Wolf (Candlewick, Mar 2013), {{ISBN|9780763663315}}\n* ''The Witch's Boy'', by Kelly Barnhill (Algonquin, Sep 2014), {{ISBN|9781616203511}}\n* ''The Nest'', by Kenneth Oppel (Simon & Schuster, Oct 2015), {{ISBN|9781481432320}}\n* ''Pax'', by Sara Pennypacker (Balzer + Bray, Feb 2016), {{ISBN|9780062377012}}\n\n== Awards ==\n* 2012 Honor, [[Bank Street College of Education#Center for Children's Literature|Irma Black Award]]<ref name=Bank>{{cite web |url=https://www.bankstreet.edu/center-childrens-literature/irma-black-award/list-winners/ |title=Past Winners (Irma Black Award)|website=www.bankstreet.edu |publisher=Bank Street College of Education |accessdate=May 8, 2016}}</ref>\n* 2013 Honor, Irma Black Award<ref name=Bank/>\n* 2013 Honor, Caldecott Medal<ref name=Cald>{{cite web |url=http://www.ala.org/alsc/awardsgrants/bookmedia/caldecottmedal/caldecotthonors/caldecottmedal |title=Caldecott Medal & Honor Books, 1938-Present |website=www.ala.org |publisher=American Library Association |accessdate=May 8, 2016}}</ref>\n* 2013 Winner, Caldecott Medal<ref name=Cald/>\n* 2015 Winner, Irma Black Award<ref name=Bank/>\n* 2015 Honor, Caldecott Medal<ref name=Cald/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist |25em |notes=\n{{efn|name=twoawards\n|1=Publication year for the British [[CILIP]] awards is the school year, roughly, September 2012 to August 2013 for consideration in 2014. Publication year for the American Library Association awards is the preceding calendar year.<br> The ALA considers only picture books for the Caldecott Medal. CILIP considers all illustrated children's books for the Greenaway and its judges recommended the eight books on its 2014 shortlist for children as old as ages 9+.<ref name=short2014/> \n}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|25em |refs=\n\n<ref name=pr2013>\n[http://www.ala.org/news/press-releases/2013/01/newbery-%E2%80%93-katherine-applegate-jon-klassen-win-newbery-caldecott-medals \"Newbery \u2013 Katherine Applegate, Jon Klassen win Newbery, Caldecott Medals\"]. ALA Press Release. 28 January 2013. Retrieved 26 June 2013.</ref>\n<ref name=caldecott>\n[http://www.ala.org/alsc/awardsgrants/bookmedia/caldecottmedal/caldecotthonors/caldecottmedal \"Caldecott Medal & Honor Books, 1938\u2013Present\"]. [[Association for Library Service to Children]] ('''ALSC'''). [[American Library Association]] ('''ALA''').<br> \n&nbsp; [http://www.ala.org/alsc/awardsgrants/bookmedia/caldecottmedal/aboutcaldecott/aboutcaldecott \"The Randolph Caldecott Medal\"]. ALSC. ALA. Retrieved 26 June 2013.</ref>\n<ref name=medal2014>\n[http://www.carnegiegreenaway.org.uk/livingarchive/title.php?id=136 (Greenaway Winner 2014)]. Living Archive: Celebrating the Carnegie and Greenaway Winners. [[Chartered Institute of Library and Information Professionals]] ('''CILIP'''). Retrieved  1 July 2014.</ref>\n<ref name=pr2014>[http://www.carnegiegreenaway.org.uk/pressdesk/press.php?release=pres_2014_winner_announce.html \"Press Desk: 'Children Don't Need Happy Endings' say winners of UK's most prestigious children's book awards\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140709032925/http://www.carnegiegreenaway.org.uk/pressdesk/press.php?release=pres_2014_winner_announce.html# |date=2014-07-09 }}. Press release 23 June 2014, with press kit. CILIP. Retrieved 1 July 2014.</ref>\n<ref name=short2014>\n[http://www.carnegiegreenaway.org.uk/pressdesk/press.php?release=pres_2014_shortcom_green.html Kate Greenaway Medal \u2013 Judges' comments on the shortlist]. Press release 18 March 2014. CILIP. Retrieved 3 July 2014.</ref>\n<ref name=short2013>\n[http://www.carnegiegreenaway.org.uk/pressdesk/press.php?release=pres_2013_shortcom_green.html Kate Greenaway Medal \u2013 Judges' comments on the shortlist]. Press release 12 March 2013. CILIP. Retrieved 3 July 2014.</ref>\n\n<ref name=PW>\nLodge, Sally (10 April 2014). [http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/childrens/childrens-book-news/article/61796-klassen-s-hat-books-hit-one-million-mark.html \"Klassen's 'Hat' Books Hit One-Million Mark\"]. ''[[Publishers Weekly]]''. Retrieved 3 July 2014.</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Animation |Children's literature |Visual arts }}\n* {{Official website}} \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140714202945/http://candlewick.com/authill.asp?b=Author&m=bio&id=3668&pix=y Klassen] at publisher Candlewick Press ([[Walker Books]] subsidiary)\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TYYQW_uCdzM&feature=player_embedded \"''I Want My Hat Back'' Book Trailer\"] \u2013 animation (video, YouTube, 5 July 2011)\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KX27V46eAYM \"An Eye for Annai\"] \u2013 animation (video, YouTube, 19 December 2005)\n* {{LCAuth|n2008082695|Jon Klassen|10|ue}} (mainly under 'Klassen, J.', previous page of Browse report)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Klassen, Jon}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Caldecott Medal winners]]\n[[Category:American children's book illustrators]]\n[[Category:Artists from Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Canadian animators]]\n[[Category:Canadian animated film directors]]\n[[Category:Canadian children's book illustrators]]\n[[Category:Canadian children's writers]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Governor General's Award-winning children's illustrators]]\n[[Category:Kate Greenaway Medal winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:Sheridan College alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Mennonite writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian Mennonites]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Jon Klassen\n| honorific-suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|CM}}\n| image        = Jon Klassen in 2016.jpg\n| caption      = Jon Klassen in 2016.\n| alt          =\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1981|11|29}}\n| birth_place  = [[Winnipeg]], Manitoba, Canada <!-- see TALK#Vital data -->\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| occupation   = Illustrator, writer\n| nationality  = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| period       = 2005\u2013present <!-- includes animation -->\n| genre        = [[Children's literature|Children's]] [[picture books]], [[animation]]\n| subject      =\n| notableworks = {{plainlist|\n* ''[[Sam and Dave Dig a Hole]]'' &nbsp;(illus.)\n* ''I Want My Hat Back''\n* ''[[This Is Not My Hat]]''\n}}\n| awards = {{awd |[[Governor General's Award for English-language children's illustration|Governor General's Award]] |2010 }} {{awd |[[Caldecott Medal]] |2013}} {{awd |[[Greenaway Medal]] |2014}}\n}}\n\n'''Jon Klassen''' {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|CM}} (born November 29, 1981)<ref name=EBkids/> is a Canadian writer and illustrator of children's books and an animator. He won both the American [[Caldecott Medal]] and the British [[Kate Greenaway Medal]] for children's book illustration, recognizing the 2012 [[picture book]] ''[[This Is Not My Hat]]'', which he also wrote.<ref name=caldecott/><ref name=pr2013/><ref name=medal2014/><ref name=pr2014/> He is the first person to win both awards for the same work.{{efn|name=twoawards}}\n\n''This Is Not My Hat'' is a companion to Klassen's preceding picture book, ''[[I Want My Hat Back|I&nbsp;Want My Hat Back]]'' (2011), which was his first as both writer and illustrator.<ref name=PW/> Both books were on the [[New York Times Best Seller list]] for more than 40 weeks; by April 2014 one or the other had been translated into 22 languages and they had jointly surpassed one million worldwide sales.<ref name=PW/> Both books were recommended for children ages 5+ by the Greenaway judges.<ref name=short2013/><ref name=short2014/> Klassen's \"hat\" trilogy was completed with the publication of ''[[We Found a Hat]]'' (2016).\n\n==Personal life==\nKlassen was born in [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]], Canada, in 1981 and grew up in [[Niagara Falls]] and [[Toronto]], Ontario.<ref name=EBkids>{{cite web |url= http://kids.britannica.com/comptons/article-9603281/Jon-Klassen |title=Jon Klassen |work=Britannica Online for Kids (kids.eb.com) |accessdate=23 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/canadian-writer-jon-klassen-wins-u-s-children-s-book-prize-1.1409756 |title=Canadian writer Jon Klassen wins U.S. children's book prize |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=28 January 2013  |accessdate=23 November 2013}}</ref> He studied animation<ref name=imundo>{{cite web|url=http://www.illustrationmundo.com/wp/417|title=Interview with Jon Klassen|last=Williams|first=Nate |publisher=Illustration Mundo (illustrationmundo.com) |accessdate=2 January 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090129125142/http://www.illustrationmundo.com/wp/417 |date=31 December 2008 |archivedate=2009-01-29}}</ref> at [[Sheridan College]], graduated in 2005,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sheridancollege.ca/Alumni/Alumni%20Profile%20Archives/Animation%20Arts%20and%20Design/Jon%20Klassen.aspx|title=Jon Klassen: Bringing Stories to Life|publisher=[[Sheridan College]]|accessdate=2 January 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111016084116/http://sheridancollege.ca/Alumni/Alumni%20Profile%20Archives/Animation%20Arts%20and%20Design/Jon%20Klassen.aspx |archivedate=2011-10-16}}</ref> and moved to [[Los Angeles]].<!--one source is Candlewick--><ref name=pr2013/>\n\nThat year<!--YouTube upload 2005-12-05--> he made an animated short with Daniel Rodrigues, ''An Eye for Annai''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ecrans.fr/Vu-sur-le-www,4775.html|title=Vu sur le www: Des canards, un \u0153il, etc.|date=4 August 2008| newspaper=[[Lib\u00e9ration]]: Ecrans |language=French |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/28/AR2007062802722.html|title=Child's Play|date=1 July 2007| newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> He worked on animation of the feature films ''[[Kung Fu Panda]]'' (2008)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.julienews.it/notizia/cultura-e-tempo-libero/a-sarmede-jon-klassen-illustratore-di-kung-fu-panda/84474_cultura-e-tempo-libero_7.html |title=A Sarmede Jon Klassen: illustratore di Kung Fu Panda |language=Italian |date=4 August 2011 |work=Cultura e Tempo Libero |publisher=JulieNews.it |accessdate=2 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508005534/http://www.julienews.it/notizia/cultura-e-tempo-libero/a-sarmede-jon-klassen-illustratore-di-kung-fu-panda/84474_cultura-e-tempo-libero_7.html |archive-date=8 May 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and ''[[Coraline (film)|Coraline]]'' (2009)<ref name=quill/> and he was art director for the 2009 animated music video of \"[[I'll Go Crazy If I Don't Go Crazy Tonight#Music videos|I'll Go Crazy If I Don't Go Crazy Tonight]]\" by U2.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&aid=73&rid=4282361&tpl=archnews&only=1|title=Irish Animator David O'Reilly Directs Latest U2 Video|date=24 July 2009|publisher=[[Irish Film and Television Network]]|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://broadwayworld.com/article/Sofa_Snark_U2_Goes_Crazy_For_Animation_20090723|title=Sofa Snark: U2 Goes 'Crazy' For Animation|last=Sims|first=James|date=23 July 2009|publisher=Broadwayworld.com|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nKlassen told Illustration Mundo at the end of 2008, \"I work at an animation studio right now on things that won't come out for years and years. ...&nbsp; it can sometimes feel like the equivalent of emptying a glass of water into a lake.\"<ref name=imundo/>\n\n==Career== <!-- \"Career\" evidently meaning books, perhaps all children's books -->\n\nIn 2010, Klassen achieved international recognition when he was awarded the [[Governor General's Award for English-language children's illustration]] for his work on the picture book ''Cats' Night Out'', written by Carolyn Stutson.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/arts-and-life/entertainment/arts/gg-literary-award-winners-stunned-overwhelmed-108625109.html|title=GG Literary Award winners 'stunned,' 'overwhelmed'|last=Wyatt|first=Nelson|date=17 November 2010 |newspaper=[[Winnipeg Free Press]] |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> He also illustrated ''The Mysterious Howling'' by Maryrose Wood, the first novel in a HarperCollins series called ''The Incorrigible Children of Ashton Place'' along with the second and third, and the first edition hardcover of the fourth novel in the series.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/11/books/review/Bookshelf-t.html|title=Children's Books; Bookshelf|last=Just|first=Julie|date=11 April 2010|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |page=BR15 |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref>{{efn|Klassen also illustrated the first two ''Incorrigible Children'' sequels, published in 2011 and 2012. Another illustrator, Eliza Wheeler, handled the paperback version of the fourth novel along with every version of the novels that were published after.}}\n\nHis first solo picture book was ''I Want My Hat Back'', published by [[Candlewick Press]] in September 2011. It features a bear looking for his hat, who finally and off-page eats the rabbit who stole it.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blog.schoollibraryjournal.com/afuse8production/2011/05/28/review-of-the-day-i-want-my-hat-back-by-jon-klassen/|title=Review of the Day: I Want My Hat Back by Jon Klassen |work=A Fuse #8 Production|last=Bird|first=Elizabeth|date=28 May 2011| publisher=[[School Library Journal]] |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]'' named it one of the \"10 Best Illustrated Children's Books for 2011\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/11/03/the-2011-best-illustrated-books/|title=The 2011 Best Illustrated Children's Books|last=Paul|first=Pamela|date=3 November 2011| newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> The book was published in September by Candlewick Press.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wired.com/geekdad/2011/09/picture-book-perfect-i-want-my-hat-back/ |title=Picture (Book) Perfect: I Want My Hat Back | website=Wired.com |last=Liu |first=Jonathan |date=20 September 2011 |accessdate=2 January 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131205114952/http://www.wired.com/geekdad/2011/09/picture-book-perfect-i-want-my-hat-back |archivedate=2013-12-05}}</ref> Klassen said of the ending, which has been called a \"subversive risk\", that \"there was no other way for it to end\". It achieved considerable commercial success, and even became an [[internet meme]] when people started \"posting their own versions of the story\".<ref name=quill>{{cite news|url=http://www.quillandquire.com/blog/index.php/2011/12/19/canadian-illustrator-jon-klassen-finds-success-with-i-want-my-hat-back/|title=Canadian illustrator Jon Klassen finds success with I Want My Hat Back|last=Flinn|first=Sue Carter|date=19 December 2011| publisher=[[Quill & Quire]] |accessdate=2 January 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527223505/http://www.quillandquire.com/blog/index.php/2011/12/19/canadian-illustrator-jon-klassen-finds-success-with-i-want-my-hat-back |archivedate=2013-05-27}}</ref> Pamela Paul praised the book in review for ''The New York Times'': \"it is a wonderful and astonishing thing, the kind of book that makes child laugh and adult chuckle, and both smile in appreciation&nbsp;... [it is] a charmingly wicked little book and the debut of a promising writer-illustrator talent.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/13/books/review/not-just-another-bear-story.html?_r=1&scp=2&sq=jon%20klassen&st=cse|title=Children's Books; Not Just Another Bear Story|last=Paul|first=Pamela|date=13 October 2011| newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> According to the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', \"the joy of this book lies in figuring out the explicit plot from the implicit details in the pictures.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/books/ct-books-hat-back-klassen,0,4024605.story|title='I Want My Hat Back' by Jon Klassen|last=Russell|first=Mary Harris| newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> There has been some discussion of the ending, however: is it appropriate in a children's book that one character kills another without repercussion? A bookseller, who \"need[ed] to go on record as saying I LOVE this book\", reported that some customers love it until they turn the last pages.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.publishersweekly.com/blogs/shelftalker/?p=6170|title=Should the Bear Eat the Rabbit?|last=Leavitt|first=Josie|date=September 2011| newspaper=[[Publishers Weekly]]|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> It was a runner-up for the American [[Geisel Award]] (books for beginning readers)<ref name=geisel>{{cite web |title= (Theodor Seuss) Geisel Award winners and honor books, 2006\u2013present |publisher= ALSC. ALA |url= http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/alsc/awardsgrants/bookmedia/geiselaward/geiselawardpastwinners/index.cfm |accessdate= 1 July 2014}}</ref> and made the Greenaway shortlist.<ref name=short2013/>\n\nKlassen modified the story in a companion book one year later, ''This Is Not My Hat'' (Candlewick, 2012). It features a little fish who steals and wears the hat of a big fish, whom the little one evades until the last pages. Finally the big fish swims back into the book, wearing the hat, with no sign of the thief. This one won the Caldecott and Greenaway Medals, from the American and British professional librarians respectively.<ref name=caldecott/><ref name=medal2014/>{{efn|name=twoawards}} According to the award committee, \"With minute changes in eyes and the slightest displacement of seagrass, Klassen's masterful illustrations tell the story the narrator doesn't know.\"<ref name=pr2013/>{{efn|Klassen also earned one of five Caldecott Honor in 2013 as the illustrator of ''Extra Yarn'', written by [[Mac Barnett]]. Only [[Leonard Weisgard]] previously illustrated two books honored in one year, 1947.}} Klassen was also awarded with a Caldecot Honor that same year for [[Extra Yarn]], only the second time that has happened.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/alsc/2013-caldecott-medal-and-honor-books|title=2013 Caldecott Medal and Honor Books|website=Association for Library Service to Children (ALSC)|language=en|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hbook.com/2013/01/blogs/calling-caldecott/caldecott-2013-post-mortem/|title=Caldecott 2013 post mortem \u2014 The Horn Book|last=Robinson|first=Lolly|date=2013-01-29|website=www.hbook.com|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> The Greenaway recognizes \"distinguished illustration in a book for children\", not necessarily a picture book. According to the British judges, \"The format and layout work perfectly to convey the underwater location with the movement of the action flowing with the water from left to right.&nbsp;... The juxtaposition of text and image works with perfect comic timing. Amazing expression is conveyed by the eyes and dramatic tension by little bubbles.\"<ref name=short2014/> The Greenaway is paired in a London announcement and presentation ceremony with the Carnegie Medal for children's literature, which recognized a controversially grim young-adult novel in 2014. According to the press release, \"both winners independently argued that children benefit from stories without happy endings.\"<ref name=pr2014/> Klassen said in his acceptance speech, \"Making a book, you're kind of going out on a limb in the belief that what you think of as a satisfying story is the same as what other people think of as a satisfying story. This doesn't mean everything in the story turns out alright for everybody, but you, as a storyteller, try and make sure it ends the way the story should end.\"<ref name=pr2014/>\n\nKlassen illustrated ''The Dark'' (2013), written by [[Lemony Snicket]], which made the Greenaway Medal shortlist of eight books alongside ''This Is Not My Hat''.<ref name=short2014/>{{efn|name=twoawards}}{{efn|Other illustrators have recently placed two books on the Greenaway shortlist, in 2008 and 2002.}}He teamed up with Mac Barnett again in 2014, on a picture book published by Candlewick, ''Sam and Dave Dig a Hole''.<ref name=PW1>Lodge, Sally (16 January 2014). [http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/childrens/childrens-book-news/article/60678-candlewick-signs-new-mac-barnett-jon-klassen-collaboration.html \"Candlewick Signs New Mac Barnett\u2013Jon Klassen Collaboration\"]. ''Publisher's Weekly''. Retrieved 8 Mar 2014.</ref>\n\nIn 2019, ''I Want My Hat Back'', ''This Is Not My Hat'', and ''We Found a Hat'' were released in a boxed set by Candlewick Press as ''Jon Klassen's Hat Box''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43671840-jon-klassen-s-hat-box|title=Jon Klassen's Hat Box|last=|first=|date=|website=Goodreads|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n<!-- 2014-07-03 intended to be complete for Engl-lang editions of books as writer OR illustrator; Works include contributions to film animation, none yet listed here. -->\n\n;Books written and illustrated\n* ''[[I Want My Hat Back]]'', by Klassen (Candlewick Press, Sep 2011) {{ISBN|9780763655983}}\n* ''[[This Is Not My Hat]]'', by Klassen (Candlewick, Oct 2012) {{ISBN|9780763655990}}\n* ''[[We Found a Hat]]'', by Klassen (Candlewick, Oct 2016) {{ISBN|9780763656003}}\n\n;With [[Mac Barnett]]\n*The Shape Trilogy\n** ''Triangle'' (Candlewick, Mar 2017), {{ISBN|9780763696030}}\n** ''Square'' (May 2018) {{ISBN|978-1406378658}}\n** ''Circle'' (Candlewick, March, 2019) {{ISBN|978-0763696085}}\n\n* ''Extra Yarn'', by Mac Barnett (Balzer + Bray, a [[HarperCollins]] imprint, Jan 2012) {{ISBN|9780061953385}}\n* ''[[Sam and Dave Dig a Hole]]'', by Barnett (Candlewick, Oct 2014), {{ISBN|9780763662295}}\n* ''The Wolf, the Duck, and the Mouse'', by Mac Barnett (Candlewick, Oct 2017), {{ISBN|9780763677541}}\n\n;Children's picture books illustrated\n* ''Cats' Night Out'', by Carolyn Stutson (Simon & Schuster, Mar 2010), {{ISBN|9781416940050}}\n* ''House Held Up By Trees'', by [[Ted Kooser]] (Candlewick, Mar 2012), {{ISBN|9780763651077}}\n* ''The Dark'', by [[Lemony Snicket]] ([[Little, Brown]], Apr 2013), {{ISBN|9780316187480}}\n\n;Other books illustrated\n* ''The Incorrigible Children of Ashton Place'' \u2013 series of novels by Maryrose Wood (published by Balzer + Bray)\n** Book I: ''The Mysterious Howling'' (Feb 2010), {{ISBN|9780061791055}}\n** Book II: ''The Hidden Gallery'' (Feb 2011), {{ISBN|9780061791123}}\n** Book III: ''The Unseen Guest'' (Mar 2012), {{ISBN|9780061791185}}\n** Book IV: ''The Interrupted Tale'' (Dec 2013), {{ISBN|9780061791222}}\n: (Book V: ''The Unmapped Sea'' (Apr 2015), {{ISBN|9780062110411}}, was illustrated by [[Eliza Wheeler]])\n* ''Vanished'', by Sheela Chari (Hyperion, July 2011), {{ISBN|9781423131632}}\n* ''The Watch that Ends the Night: Voices from the Titanic'', by Allan Wolf (Candlewick, Mar 2013), {{ISBN|9780763663315}}\n* ''The Witch's Boy'', by Kelly Barnhill (Algonquin, Sep 2014), {{ISBN|9781616203511}}\n* ''The Nest'', by Kenneth Oppel (Simon & Schuster, Oct 2015), {{ISBN|9781481432320}}\n* ''Pax'', by Sara Pennypacker (Balzer + Bray, Feb 2016), {{ISBN|9780062377012}}\n\n== Awards ==\n* 2012 Honor, [[Bank Street College of Education#Center for Children's Literature|Irma Black Award]]<ref name=Bank>{{cite web |url=https://www.bankstreet.edu/center-childrens-literature/irma-black-award/list-winners/ |title=Past Winners (Irma Black Award)|website=www.bankstreet.edu |publisher=Bank Street College of Education |accessdate=May 8, 2016}}</ref>\n* 2013 Honor, Irma Black Award<ref name=Bank/>\n* 2013 Honor, Caldecott Medal<ref name=Cald>{{cite web |url=http://www.ala.org/alsc/awardsgrants/bookmedia/caldecottmedal/caldecotthonors/caldecottmedal |title=Caldecott Medal & Honor Books, 1938-Present |website=www.ala.org |publisher=American Library Association |accessdate=May 8, 2016}}</ref>\n* 2013 Winner, Caldecott Medal<ref name=Cald/>\n* 2015 Winner, Irma Black Award<ref name=Bank/>\n* 2015 Honor, Caldecott Medal<ref name=Cald/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist |25em |notes=\n{{efn|name=twoawards\n|1=Publication year for the British [[CILIP]] awards is the school year, roughly, September 2012 to August 2013 for consideration in 2014. Publication year for the American Library Association awards is the preceding calendar year.<br> The ALA considers only picture books for the Caldecott Medal. CILIP considers all illustrated children's books for the Greenaway and its judges recommended the eight books on its 2014 shortlist for children as old as ages 9+.<ref name=short2014/> \n}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|25em |refs=\n\n<ref name=pr2013>\n[http://www.ala.org/news/press-releases/2013/01/newbery-%E2%80%93-katherine-applegate-jon-klassen-win-newbery-caldecott-medals \"Newbery \u2013 Katherine Applegate, Jon Klassen win Newbery, Caldecott Medals\"]. ALA Press Release. 28 January 2013. Retrieved 26 June 2013.</ref>\n<ref name=caldecott>\n[http://www.ala.org/alsc/awardsgrants/bookmedia/caldecottmedal/caldecotthonors/caldecottmedal \"Caldecott Medal & Honor Books, 1938\u2013Present\"]. [[Association for Library Service to Children]] ('''ALSC'''). [[American Library Association]] ('''ALA''').<br> \n&nbsp; [http://www.ala.org/alsc/awardsgrants/bookmedia/caldecottmedal/aboutcaldecott/aboutcaldecott \"The Randolph Caldecott Medal\"]. ALSC. ALA. Retrieved 26 June 2013.</ref>\n<ref name=medal2014>\n[http://www.carnegiegreenaway.org.uk/livingarchive/title.php?id=136 (Greenaway Winner 2014)]. Living Archive: Celebrating the Carnegie and Greenaway Winners. [[Chartered Institute of Library and Information Professionals]] ('''CILIP'''). Retrieved  1 July 2014.</ref>\n<ref name=pr2014>[http://www.carnegiegreenaway.org.uk/pressdesk/press.php?release=pres_2014_winner_announce.html \"Press Desk: 'Children Don't Need Happy Endings' say winners of UK's most prestigious children's book awards\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140709032925/http://www.carnegiegreenaway.org.uk/pressdesk/press.php?release=pres_2014_winner_announce.html# |date=2014-07-09 }}. Press release 23 June 2014, with press kit. CILIP. Retrieved 1 July 2014.</ref>\n<ref name=short2014>\n[http://www.carnegiegreenaway.org.uk/pressdesk/press.php?release=pres_2014_shortcom_green.html Kate Greenaway Medal \u2013 Judges' comments on the shortlist]. Press release 18 March 2014. CILIP. Retrieved 3 July 2014.</ref>\n<ref name=short2013>\n[http://www.carnegiegreenaway.org.uk/pressdesk/press.php?release=pres_2013_shortcom_green.html Kate Greenaway Medal \u2013 Judges' comments on the sh